If your organization keeps any physical items on site that are currently unused but expected to be used or sold, it uses storage for these items. Your storage can be as small as a shelf with dozens of office supplies in a back office or as large as multiple physical warehouses with billions of goods situated in different regions or even countries.{br}
If you want to track your stored items in Acumatica ERP, you can use the functionality of warehouses and locations and choose the approach that best fits your business. You can configure a single warehouse or multiple warehouses. Within each warehouse, you can define a single location or multiple locations. In this topic, you will find general information about warehouses in Acumatica ERP.{br}{TOC} ==Warehouses in Acumatica ERP== In Acumatica ERP, a warehouse does not necessarily represent a physical building where your inventory is stocked. You can divide a large physical storage space into multiple areas and define each area as a warehouse in Acumatica ERP. A warehouse can even be virtual: for example, you might consider all goods that are on the way from the supplier to you as being located in a goods-in-transit warehouse.{br}
You can configure any of the following warehouse structures:[anchor|#_35f885f0-c5df-4081-a57a-d30d433baf0c] *One warehouse with one location: You use this structure when you have a small variety of inventory items and it’s not important for you to track in which room or on which shelf these items are stored. For more information, see [[#_ee36f3b7-b245-4beb-98e0-07e76b0e6e7c|Basic Warehouse Structure]. *One warehouse with multiple locations: You use this structure when you have one space and need to track the locations within it and the items in those locations. For example, you might have one physical room with many numbered shelves, or multiple rooms with shelves and boxes, and you may want to register in the system the exact placement of each inventory item. *Multiple warehouses with one location in each warehouse: You use this structure when you store items in multiple physical rooms or buildings, and each storage place holds a small number of items, which warehouse employees can easily find without knowing a more specific location of items. *Multiple warehouses with multiple locations in each warehouse: You use this structure when you have a distributed network of large warehouses that hold a wide variety of goods in different locations. *Multiple warehouses with one location or multiple locations in each warehouse: You use this structure when you have multiple warehouses, which vary in terms of whether they have multiple locations within them. For example, when you have a large distribution center from where goods are sent to multiple small warehouses.
For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Multiple_Warehouses|Multiple Warehouses] and [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Warehouse_Locations|Warehouse Locations].[anchor|#_ee36f3b7-b245-4beb-98e0-07e76b0e6e7c] ==Basic Warehouse Structure== When you have just a few items to keep in a small storage area, you can use the basic functionality of warehouses in Acumatica ERP. The basic functionality is available when you have the following license settings on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form:[anchor|#_087c12ff-cd47-43b9-b861-ada15b13d190] *The ''Inventory'' feature is enabled. *The ''Multiple Warehouses'' and ''Multiple Warehouse Locations'' features (which provide more advanced functionality) are disabled.
The system creates the default warehouse and assigns ''MAIN'' as the warehouse ID when you configure the settings of the Inventory module on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. ((({S:Hint}The ID of the only warehouse, ''MAIN'', is not displayed on data entry forms for simplicity. However, this warehouse ID will be used automatically in all inventory transactions. ))){br}
If needed, you can change the identifier of the ''MAIN'' warehouse on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form by clicking '''Actions''' > '''Change ID''' on the form toolbar and specifying a new identifier in the dialog box that opens.{br}
When the ''Multiple Warehouses'' feature is not enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] form, the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form displays only the '''Warehouse ID''' box. The following settings are specified for the default warehouse but are hidden from this form:[anchor|#_884ee7a7-e307-4ed8-be29-931132a439e8] *'''Replenishment Class''': ''Purchase'' * '''Default Cost of Returns''': ''Average''
For the default warehouse, the system creates a default location that the goods will be received to and issued from and assigns ''MAIN'' as the location ID. The location settings are not displayed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form if the ''Multiple Warehouse Locations'' feature is disabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] form, but the ''MAIN'' location has the following settings: [anchor|#_a06ea460-5902-413c-996d-eb2b2835f3b5] *'''Active''': Selected *'''Include in Qty. Available''': Selected *'''Cost Separately''': Cleared *'''Sales Allowed''': Selected *'''Receipts Allowed''': Selected *'''Transfers Allowed''': Selected *'''Assembly Allowed''': Selected
==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Multiple_Warehouses|Multiple Warehouses] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Warehouse_Locations|Warehouse Locations] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000])

When your organization has multiple buildings, storage rooms, or other facilities for storing inventory items, you can create multiple warehouses in Acumatica ERP to process inventory appropriately for each warehouse.{br}
With the ''Multiple Warehouses'' feature enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can create any number of warehouses, even virtual warehouses, in the way that best fits your business with specific settings for each warehouse. In this topic, you will read about multiple warehouses in Acumatica ERP.{br}{TOC} ==Configuration of Multiple Warehouses== After you have enabled the ''Multiple Warehouses'' feature on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form and configured inventory preferences (see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Configuration_of_Basic_Inventory|Configuration of Basic Inventory]), you can create as many warehouses as you need on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form.{br}
In Acumatica ERP, if you have multiple warehouses defined, you can perform transfers between warehouses, relocating stock items as needed, or you can use one warehouse as a source of replenishment for other warehouses by having purchased goods delivered to only this warehouse and then transferring the goods to other warehouses.{br}
To create and configure a warehouse, you do the following:[anchor|#_16f3d782-aa70-40c3-a626-d05fc00f8c64] #Optional: On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_20_00|Segmented Keys] ([~/?ScreenId=CS202000|CS202000]) form, you review the default settings of the ''INSITE'' segmented key, which is used for warehouse identifiers, and adjust the settings of the key to meet your needs. You can configure identifiers to have one segment or multiple segments. If you are going to use multiple segments, you need to determine how many segments (and of what length) will be used, whether the segments should be validated (and if so, what kind of values are allowed), and whether an auto-numbered segment will be used. For details on segmented keys, see [HelpRoot_Administration\CS__con_Identifier_Segmentation|Segmented Identifiers]. #On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form, you create a warehouse and specify its settings, as described in [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Warehouse|To Create a Warehouse]. #:((({S:Hint}If you want to specify warehouse-specific General Ledger accounts, make sure that all the necessary accounts have been created in the system before you start creating warehouses. ))) #Optional: On the '''Location Table''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form, you specify the locations for the warehouse. For more information about warehouse locations, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Warehouse_Locations|Warehouse Locations]. #:((({S:Hint}The '''Location Table''' tab is displayed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form only if the ''Multiple Warehouse Locations'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] form. ))) #Optional: You configure warehouse security, such as restricting access to forms based on user roles and configuring the visibility of particular warehouses to appropriate users. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_and_Warehouse_Security|Warehouse Security].
==Warehouse as a Source of GL Accounts and Subaccounts for Posting Classes== A posting class, which is specified for each stock or non-stock item, is a group of settings that provide the default values for the purchase, sales, and inventory transactions with the item and define how these transactions will be posted to the General Ledger. One of these default values is the source of General Ledger accounts and subaccounts to be used for the item, which can be a source of default General Ledger accounts and subaccounts for an inventory item. If you store inventory items of the same category in multiple warehouses, and each warehouse has specific General Ledger accounts and subaccounts specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form, you can use a warehouse as a source of default General Ledger accounts and subaccounts for an inventory item. You define the source of accounts and subaccounts that the system should use in a posting class.{br}
For example, you can have one inventory account for each warehouse. In this case, you can specify the needed inventory account in the warehouse settings on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form and specify the warehouse as the source of inventory account in the posting class on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form.{br}
For details about how to specify a warehouse as a source of General Ledger accounts and subaccounts for a posting class, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Use_Warehouse_GL_Accounts_and_Subaccounts_in_Posting_Classes|To Use Warehouse General Ledger Accounts and Subaccounts in a Posting Class]. ==Warehouse-Specific Settings for Stock Items== If the details of stocking a particular inventory item vary in different warehouses, you specify the details for the item at each warehouse on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. You can view these warehouse-specific settings of items on the '''Warehouse Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. {br}
For each stock item at a particular warehouse, you can specify the following:[anchor|#_70a75297-0c49-4d13-a94f-9362dcfde769] *The default locations for issuing and receiving the item at this warehouse *The inventory account and subaccount to be used for the stock item at this warehouse *The ABC code and movement class assigned to the item when it is at this warehouse *The replenishment settings for the item when it is stocked in this warehouse *The cost statistics related to this item at this warehouse
In the following cases, the system adds a new record to the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form:[anchor|#_7b50a17c-9c56-4974-b283-843a50add4b8] *When any user specifies or changes the default warehouse for an inventory item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. *When any user releases the first inventory receipt to a new warehouse (or other transaction that increases inventory, such as the receiving part of an inventory transfer).
==Warehouse-Specific Prices== If you have multiple warehouses defined in the system, you can define warehouse-specific sales prices and vendor prices for items. You can define the price of the item and select the warehouse for this price. If no warehouse is specified for a price on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_20_20_10|Vendor Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AP202010|AP202010]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_00|Sales Prices] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202000|AR202000]) forms, this price is applied to all warehouses that are defined in the system. A price that has a warehouse specified has a higher priority than a price of the same type with no warehouse selected. For example, a promotional customer price that is specific to a warehouse has a higher priority than a promotional customer price with no warehouse specified. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Financials\AR__CON_PriceLists|Multiple Price Lists] and [HelpRoot_Financials\AP__CON_Vendor_PriceLists|Maintaining Vendor Price Lists]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Configuration_of_Basic_Inventory|Configuration of Basic Inventory] *[HelpRoot_Financials\AR__CON_PriceLists|Multiple Price Lists] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_20_00|Segmented Keys] ([~/?ScreenId=CS202000|CS202000]) *[HelpRoot_Financials\AP__CON_Vendor_PriceLists|Maintaining Vendor Price Lists] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Use_Warehouse_GL_Accounts_and_Subaccounts_in_Posting_Classes|To Use Warehouse General Ledger Accounts and Subaccounts in a Posting Class] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000])

In Acumatica ERP, you can configure multiple locations in each warehouse to best fit the logistics established in your company. You can reserve specific locations for sales, receipts, transfers, goods to be returned to vendors, and goods returned by customers.{br}
You can assign different pick priorities to locations, to empty certain locations more quickly while using others less frequently.{br}
In this topic, you will find information about the creation and use of warehouse locations in Acumatica ERP.{br}{TOC} ==Default Warehouse Locations== For each warehouse created in the system, the system automatically creates a default location (with the ''MAIN'' location ID, which you can change later) that the goods will be received to and issued from. The ''MAIN'' location has the following settings on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form:[anchor|#_7550d797-3671-4129-a5b7-6f79118fa38b] *'''Active''': Selected *'''Include in Qty. Available''': Selected *'''Cost Separately''': Cleared *'''Sales Allowed''': Selected *'''Receipts Allowed''': Selected *'''Transfers Allowed''': Selected *'''Assembly Allowed''': Selected ((({S:Hint}These location settings are displayed on the '''Location Table''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form only if the ''Multiple Warehouse Locations'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form; if it is not enabled, the tab is not shown on the form but the settings listed above are used internally. ))) ==Configuration of Warehouse Locations== With the ''Multiple Warehouse Locations'' feature enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can configure multiple locations for each warehouse. If it is enabled, on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form, you can view and change the settings of the default location and define the other locations for each warehouse.{br}
You do the following to create and configure warehouse locations in Acumatica ERP:[anchor|#_d7c2f705-dd65-491b-af60-a7261263a4c8] #Optional: On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_20_00|Segmented Keys] ([~/?ScreenId=CS202000|CS202000]) form, you review the structure of the ''INLOCATION'' segmented key, which defines the identifiers for warehouse locations. If you want to create a hierarchy of locations (site, aisle, pallet, bin, and so forth), you can configure location identifiers that consist of multiple segments, with each segment denoting a specific level in this hierarchy. For example, suppose that you have three racks, each with four shelves, in a warehouse. A location identifier can look as follows: ''Rn-SHm'', where ''Rn'' is the number of the rack (such as ''R2'') and ''SHm'' is the number of the shelf in the rack (such as ''SH4''). For more information about segmented keys, see [HelpRoot_Administration\CS__con_Identifier_Segmentation|Segmented Identifiers]. #On the '''Location Table''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form for each warehouse, you add each location and specify its settings, as described in [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Warehouse_Location|To Create Warehouse Locations]. You add as many locations as you need. #:((({S:Hint}To create similar configurations of locations in multiple warehouses, you can export the location table to an Excel file (with the <tt>.xlsx</tt> format) and import settings from the file to the same warehouse or another warehouse and change the setting as needed. For details on importing the settings from an Excel file, see [HelpRoot_GettingStarted\Exporting_to_Excel|Integration with Excel]. ))) #Optional: On the '''Location Table''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form, you specify the default locations (which simplify data entry on purchase receipts and sales orders) for inventory operations in the following boxes: #*'''Receiving Location''': The default receiving location for stock items in the warehouse. #*'''Shipping Location''': The default shipping location for the warehouse. #*'''RMA Location''': The location used for all operations involving return merchandise authorization (RMA). The returned goods will be delivered to the location specified in this box, regardless of the warehouse location selected by default for the receipt of these goods. #*'''Drop-Ship Location''': The location used for drop-ship orders and all inventory documents that are automatically generated for drop-ship orders. #Optional: In the '''Location Entry''' box in the Summary area of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form, you specify the option that indicates whether you want to allow users to add new locations on the fly when they are entering inventory documents. You can view locations added by users on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form and modify their settings if needed.
==Priorities of Warehouse Locations== If you store inventory items of the same type (such as apples) in multiple locations within the same warehouse, the system has to find the appropriate warehouse location from which to pick the items when a user creates a shipment for a sales order. For each location, you can specify the pick priority, which will help the system to select a correct location if it finds multiple locations that have the item.{br}
For example, suppose that you store a dairy product with that can be kept for one week. You purchase this dairy product every day and store it in two locations of the warehouse: A and B. In Location A, you store a variant of the dairy product that can be kept from five to seven days. In Location B, you store a variant of the dairy produce that can be kept from two to four days. You can assign the highest pick priority to Location B so that dairy product with an earlier expiration date are shipped first.{br}
The way the system finds a location from which the line item&rsquo;s ordered quantity will be picked depends on whether the applicable sales order is related to a project and task and on the location settings—whether the '''Project ID''' and '''Task ID''' columns are filled in for the location on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form—as follows:[anchor|#_cc32c50c-76e4-4745-bd08-7901fa87e14a] *If the sales order is not related to any project: The system searches for the applicable location among all available locations and selects the location with the highest pick priority. *If the sales order is related to a project and a task—that is, if a project ID is specified for the sales order on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form and a task ID is specified for a sales order line on this form): The system selects the first applicable location it finds by using the following search priority (from highest to lowest): **A location for which the project ID and task ID are the same as the project ID and task ID of the sales order **A location whose project ID is the same as the project ID of the sales order and whose task ID is unspecified **A location for which the project ID and task ID are not specified **A location for which the project ID is the same as the project ID of a sales order and for which the task ID differs from the task ID of the sales order line
If both sales orders related to projects and sales orders unrelated to projects are used in your system, and you want to ensure that locations in shipments match project codes in sales orders, we recommend that you specify the lowest pick priority (that is, the highest value in the '''Pick Priority''' column on the '''Location Table''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form) for those locations that are associated with projects. As a result, for the sales orders that are unrelated to projects, the system will search among the non-project locations first; if no applicable non-project location has been found, the system will continue to search in the locations that are related to projects. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Configuration_of_Basic_Inventory|Configuration of Basic Inventory] *[HelpRoot_GettingStarted\Exporting_to_Excel|Integration with Excel] *[HelpRoot_Administration\CS__con_Identifier_Segmentation|Segmented Identifiers] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Warehouses|Warehouses in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Multiple_Warehouses|Multiple Warehouses] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Warehouse_Location|To Create Warehouse Locations]

An organization can have multiple warehouses in Acumatica ERP, and different groups of employees may work with these warehouses in the system. To limit in the system the set of employees who work with a particular warehouse, you can create restriction groups to display the warehouse for only employees who are responsible for tasks that involve this warehouse. If the employees who work with the same warehouse perform only specific tasks (such as accepting goods and creating purchase orders), you can provide these employees with access to only the forms that they should use.{br}
In this topic, you can find information about configuring the security of warehouses in Acumatica ERP.[anchor|#_5ff7281a-de00-416b-8579-a326526bab78]((({S:Hint}In Acumatica ERP, you can configure groups with direct and inverse restriction. In this topic, for simplicity, groups with direct restriction are used in examples. You can use inverse restriction groups in the same way as you use direct restriction groups. For details on the types of restriction groups, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Types_of_Restriction_Groups|Types of Restriction Groups]. ))){br}{TOC} ==Usage Scenarios== The most common scenarios of managing the security of warehouses are the following:[anchor|#_4bfda738-cf0c-4f2b-9077-d6ff655fa566] *Managing access to forms based on employees&rsquo; functional roles: If employees perform specific tasks (such as receiving goods and creating purchase orders), you can provide the employees access to the forms they use in their work, and revoke access for forms that they shouldn&rsquo;t use. For details, see [[#_29384b43-8e49-46d4-8c83-0a2c8801139d|Access to Forms Based on Roles]. *Managing the visibility of particular warehouses by user: If you have created multiple warehouses in Acumatica ERP, you can restrict the visibility of warehouses to users on forms by using restriction groups. For details, see [[#_4134d0c6-086f-45f5-b43f-a3d0dbe76eec|Visibility of Warehouses by User]. *:((({S:Hint}You can create and manage multiple warehouses in Acumatica ERP only if the ''Multiple Warehouses'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. )))
In addition to managing the visibility of warehouses in whole, you can restrict the visibility of particular inventory items. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\RS__con_Restriction_Groups_for_Subitems|Inventory Item Security].[anchor|#_29384b43-8e49-46d4-8c83-0a2c8801139d] ==Access to Forms Based on Roles== By using the forms of the User Security submodule, you can use user roles in Acumatica ERP to give employees access to forms related to working with warehouses. A role can correspond to an area of responsibility for an employee who performs warehouse-related tasks, such as creating purchase orders, accepting goods, and preparing replenishment. If needed, you can assign multiple roles to an employee. For more information about user roles, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access].{br}
Consider the following examples of roles for employees who work with inventory and order management:[anchor|#_3aed05a7-1529-4e93-8536-70cafc558db4] *''Supervisor'': A role for an employee who configures the Inventory submodule and manages work with the submodule. This role should have access to the forms related to inventory processes, such as the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. *''Data Entry Clerk'': A role for an employee who creates documents on data entry forms. You should provide access to such forms as [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_20_00|Issues] ([~/?ScreenId=IN302000|IN302000]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_10_00|Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=IN301000|IN301000]), or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_40_00|Transfers] ([~/?ScreenId=IN304000|IN304000]). *''Purchasing Manager'': A role for an employee who is responsible for replenishment. For this role, you should provide access to the '''Replenishment''' node of the '''Processes''' tab of the Inventory module. [anchor|#_4134d0c6-086f-45f5-b43f-a3d0dbe76eec] ==Visibility of Warehouses by User== By default, all employees who have access to forms of the inventory and order management modules can see all warehouses created in the system. By using the forms of the Row-Level Security module, you can configure the system so that each warehouse is displayed only to users who work with this warehouse. You can use restriction groups to set up the visibility of warehouses to employees. For details on restriction groups, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Overview_of_Restriction_Groups|Restriction Groups in Acumatica ERP].{br}
For example, suppose that your system has the ''Wholesale'' and ''Retail'' warehouses defined, and you need to configure the visibility of these warehouses to users as follows:[anchor|#_8a8cd601-eb3c-4042-b8d7-32a182dd9acc] *User S is a supervisor who should configure and manage both warehouses. *User C1 is a clerk who enters documents for the ''Wholesale'' warehouse. *User C2 is a clerk who enters documents for the ''Retail'' warehouse.
To configure the visibility of warehouses according to this example, you do the following on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_00|Warehouse Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102000|IN102000]) form:[anchor|#_3d9fa191-30d8-42a0-8030-9c8f57fcfbfa] #You create two restriction groups of type ''A'' (with direct restriction): ''Group 1'' for the ''Wholesale'' warehouse, and ''Group 2'' for the ''Retail'' warehouse. #In Group 1, you include User S, User C1, and the ''Wholesale'' warehouse. #In Group 2, you include User S, User C2, and the ''Retail'' warehouse.
The resulting visibility of warehouses will be the following:[anchor|#_edda2fc2-790d-43d1-8446-7928a3efb85e] *User S can see both the ''Wholesale'' and ''Retail'' warehouses. *User C1 can see only the ''Wholesale'' warehouse. *User C2 can see only the ''Retail'' warehouse. [anchor|#_7ed1ab5a-0a06-4b9a-a2ec-4491a9f59cb4] ==Forms for Warehouse Security== In the following table, you can find the list of forms that you can use to manage restriction groups with warehouses and tasks that you can solve by using each form.[anchor|#_4d607671-c1fd-412f-a1ea-560c07f9fcc7] ===Forms for Warehouse Security=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="50%" ! Tasks !width="50%" ! Forms |- | To initially configure the visibility of a warehouse to users | [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_00|Warehouse Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102000|IN102000]) |- | To change the visibility of a warehouse in multiple restriction groups | [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_10|Restriction Groups by Warehouse] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102010|IN102010]) |- | To change the visibility of warehouses to a user in multiple restriction groups | [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_35|Restriction Groups by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201035|SM201035]) |}[anchor|#_f3675cc6-b773-4347-812f-4284852d2ed6] For information about how to add or remove objects from a restriction group, see [HelpRoot_Administration\RS__con_Operations_Restriction_Groups|Operations with Restriction Groups]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Overview_of_Restriction_Groups|Restriction Groups in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Types_of_Restriction_Groups|Types of Restriction Groups] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_35|Restriction Groups by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201035|SM201035]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_10|Restriction Groups by Warehouse] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102010|IN102010]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_20_00|Warehouse Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN102000|IN102000])

Before you start processing documents related to inventory, you must configure basic settings (that is, the minimum settings for the Inventory module in Acumatica ERP to work correctly). The basic settings include posting classes, units of measure, item classes, and inventory items.{br}
In this chapter, you will read about configuration of basic settings in the Inventory module. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#_aacdb93b-627a-4233-a8d5-bedab30b534e] {| class="checklist invisiblechecklist" | width="100%" |- | [anchor|#_7def23d0-d706-4de8-b2b8-131c32d9ba8c] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Configuration_of_Basic_Inventory|Configuration of Basic Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_GL_Accounts_Inventory|Posting Settings in the Inventory Module] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Reason_Codes__Definition_and_Usage|Reason Codes for Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Posting_Classes__Definition_and_Usage|Posting Classes in Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Units_of_Measure_and_Conversions|Units of Measure and Conversions] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_BaseWeightVolumeUOMs|Units of Weight and Volume] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Items|Inventory Items] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Classes|Item Classes] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Stock_Items|Stock Items] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Non-Stock_Item_Support|Non-Stock Items in the Inventory Module] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Restriction_Groups_for_Subitems|Inventory Item Security]
