An important part of the configuration of the Inventory module is to specify the posting settings—that is, the General Ledger accounts and subaccounts for inventory entities (such as stock items) and the rules determining how the system will select an account in specific transactions. In Acumatica ERP, you can create posting classes and reason codes that provide the default General Ledger accounts and subaccounts, or you can use warehouse- or item-specific accounts and subaccounts. In this topic, you will find information about the types of accounts used in the Inventory module, the system entities for which you can define accounts and subaccounts, and the posting settings.{br}{TOC} ==Configuration of Posting Settings== Before you start configuring the Inventory module, you must create all necessary General Ledger accounts and subaccounts that the system will use for inventory transactions. For the description of the accounts and subaccounts used in inventory, see [[#_322e5ef6-efdc-4501-b275-20402435782a|General Ledger Accounts in Inventory].{br}
During the configuration of the Inventory module, you specify the following posting settings:[anchor|#_a955560f-9e2d-48f0-bed9-ad4918177d48] *Reason codes: Reason codes are used with manually entered inventory transactions to track the reasons for these transactions. Reason codes provide offset accounts (with offset subaccounts if they are used in your system) to be used to post the transactions to General Ledger. For details, see [[#_012fc657-1b5b-4f2b-9d51-aa8a0c199ee4|Reason Codes]. *Posting classes: Posting classes are used to provide default General Ledger accounts and subaccounts for inventory items. For details, see [[#_6fb00522-8970-4d8f-b296-13f2039bafa8|Posting Classes]. *Integration settings between General Ledger and Inventory: The settings used to configure the level of integration between the Inventory and General Ledger modules. For details, see [[#_e4d70d48-be97-4c5d-a1d5-79dd9a9054e7|Inventory–General Ledger Integration Settings].
We recommend that you thoroughly plan inventory accounts during the initial configuration of the Inventory module. But in rare situations you may need to change the accounts after users have started processing inventory documents. For more information, see [[#_f8432eca-f9bd-44a4-a381-4c2f736aa305|Change of an Inventory Account for an Item].[anchor|#_322e5ef6-efdc-4501-b275-20402435782a] ==General Ledger Accounts in Inventory== In the Inventory module, you can specify General Ledger accounts in settings of the following entities: warehouses (if you use multiple warehouses in the system), posting classes (which can be used for stock or non-stock items), stock items, and non-stock items. You can use the following General Ledger accounts to record inventory transactions:[anchor|#_3626e431-e064-478a-89ff-62e91ee0efb7] *Inventory/Accrual account: An account that is one of the following: **An ''asset'' account to keep the inventory balance resulting from transactions with a stock item (if the account is specified for a stock item or for a posting class used for a stock item) or transactions in a specific warehouse (if the account is specified in the warehouse settings). The cost of the items will be debited to the inventory account when the items are received, and credited when the items are issued from inventory. **A ''liability'' account to be used for non-stock items as the expense accrual account (if the account is specified for a non-stock item or for a posting class to be used for non-stock items). The cost of purchased non-stock items will be credited to this account, and when a bill is created, the cost will be debited to this account. *Sales account: The income account to record sales for a warehouse, posting class, stock item, or non-stock item. *COGS/Expense account: An account that is one of the following: **If the account is specified for a warehouse, stock item, or posting class for stock items, an expense account used as the cost of goods sold (COGS) account. This account will accrue the cost of goods sold once a sales order is released. The cost of items sold is debited to the account when items are issued for sale from inventory. **If the account is specified for a non-stock item or for a posting class to be used for non-stock items or labor items, this is the expense account used for transactions with these items. *Standard Cost Variance account: The ''expense'' account to be used for a warehouse, stock item, or posting class for stock items to record any differences between the currently effective standard cost and the cost on the bill for the specified quantities of items. This account is used only for transactions associated with inventory items for which the standard cost valuation method is assigned. *Standard Cost Revaluation account: The ''expense'' account to be used for a warehouse, stock item, or posting class for stock items to record the differences in inventory value estimated by using the pending standard cost and the currently effective standard cost for the quantities on hand of a stock item. Revaluation is performed at the moment of updating standard costs—that is, when the currently effective standard cost becomes the last standard cost, and the pending cost becomes the effective standard cost. This account is used only for transactions associated with inventory items for which the standard cost valuation method is assigned. *PO accrual account: The ''liability'' account to be used for a warehouse, stock item, or posting class to accrue amounts on purchase orders related to the warehouse or stock item. Whenever receipts linked to purchase orders are released, the system generates transactions between the purchase order accrual account and the inventory account. *Purchase Price Variance account: The ''expense'' account to be used for a warehouse, stock item, non-stock item, or posting class for a stock or non-stock item to record any differences between the extended price on the purchase receipt and the extended price on the Accounts Payable bill. This account is used only for transactions associated with inventory items for which any of the valuation methods except for the standard cost valuation method is assigned. *Landed Cost Variance account: The ''expense'' account to be used for a warehouse, stock item, or posting class for a stock item to record any differences in landed costs between the landed costs amounts specified on purchase receipts and the amounts on inventory receipts. *Deferral account: The account to be used to hold the deferred amount until it is fully recognized. The account type should be specified as follows: **A liability account for a deferral code of the revenue type **An asset account for a deferral code of the expense type [anchor|#_012fc657-1b5b-4f2b-9d51-aa8a0c199ee4] ==Reason Codes== If inventory transactions are generated from the Purchase Orders or Sales Orders module, the system will use the PO Accrual account (for purchase receipts) or the COGS account (for sales orders). The offset account and subaccount for a receipt, issue, adjustment, or transfer are determined by the document&rsquo;s reason code, which is selected depending on the specific transaction being performed. For different types of inventory transactions, different types of offset accounts should be selected. Reason codes also can be used to gather statistics about specific inventory transactions.{br}
You define reason codes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) form. Each reason code is associated with the type of inventory transaction for which it will be used. For each type of inventory transaction, you can create multiple reason codes, if necessary, to further categorize transactions within their types. By using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form, you can define the reason codes used most frequently with each type of transaction as the default reason code for this type of transactions.{br}
For more information on using reason codes, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Reason_Codes__Definition_and_Usage|Reason Codes for Inventory].[anchor|#_6fb00522-8970-4d8f-b296-13f2039bafa8] ==Posting Classes== In Acumatica ERP, you can use posting classes to provide the default accounts and subaccounts for items of the class; in this case, the accounts specified in the posting class are used for assigning the default General Ledger accounts for items. You create posting classes for stock and non-stock items by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form.{br}
On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form, you can assign a posting class to an item class; the system will use this posting class as the default posting class for inventory items of this item class. If needed, you can assign a specific posting class (instead of the default one) to a particular stock item by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form, and to a particular non-stock item by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form. For more information on managing item classes, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Classes|Item Classes].{br}
A posting class defines the rules for selecting General Ledger accounts and subaccounts to be used for transactions with items assigned to the posting class. When a transaction with an inventory item is created, multiple similar accounts are involved. For example, when a stock item is received at a particular warehouse, its cost (a debit amount) can be recorded to either the inventory account associated with the warehouse or the inventory account associated with the inventory item. Subaccounts for various types of transactions can be combined from multiple involved subaccounts, depending on the policies established in your organization. You can select General Ledger accounts and subaccount segment values from the following sources:[anchor|#_ecb0992b-8938-4e9d-b6d4-fe28e506955a] *Inventory item *Warehouse *Posting class
The posting class also provides the account and subaccount to be used if the source of General Ledger accounts for a transaction is a posting class itself.{br}
For more details about using posting classes, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Posting_Classes__Definition_and_Usage|Posting Classes in Inventory].[anchor|#_e4d70d48-be97-4c5d-a1d5-79dd9a9054e7] ==Inventory–General Ledger Integration Settings== The settings used to configure the integration between the Inventory and General Ledger modules are located on the '''General Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. The following check boxes are available: [anchor|#_329ae256-431a-4bc3-8dc4-a9fd85958fac] *'''Update GL''': If this check box is selected, transactions originating in the Inventory module will update the General Ledger module. If this check box is cleared, inventory transactions do not update the General Ledger module, and the inventory can be maintained independently from the General Ledger module. *'''Post Summary on Updating GL''': If this check box is selected, the system will include in the batch only summary information (for the account–subaccount pair). If this check box is cleared, the detailed information for each document line will be included in the batch generated for the document. *'''Automatically Post on Release''': If this check box is cleared, inventory transactions will not be automatically posted to the General Ledger module on release of nventory documents; the inventory transactions should be posted through the General Ledger module. If this check box is selected, inventory transactions will be posted on the release of inventory documents. [anchor|#_f8432eca-f9bd-44a4-a381-4c2f736aa305] ==Change of an Inventory Account for an Item== We recommend that you carefully plan inventory accounts and avoid changing the inventory account for an item after you have started processing transactions with the item. ((({S:Hint}If you change the posting class for an item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form, the General Ledger accounts are repopulated in the item from the new posting class, which may affect the inventory account that is used for transaction processing with the item if the source of the inventory account is set to ''Inventory Item'' for the posting class on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form. ))) If you decide to define a specific inventory account for some item-warehouse combinations, we also recommend that you do this during initial configuration.{br}
If you need to change the inventory account for an item after you have started processing transactions, the following will happen to inventory transactions after you change the inventory account in an item&rsquo;s settings:[anchor|#_b1bf217a-66f8-4ab2-b747-4da71633ad77] *Inventory receipts, as well as other transactions that increase inventory, will start to process to the new inventory account retrieved from settings. *Inventory issues will continue to clear the old inventory account until its balance is zero. *Inventory adjustments will be processed to the new inventory account retrieved from settings.
If you want to transfer the item&rsquo;s balance to the new inventory account, we recommend that you do the following:[anchor|#_0739da8f-7689-4521-94ee-4d6ef8f68a9d] #You create a temporary clearing asset account in the General Ledger module. #You create an issue reason code for the old inventory account and a receipt reason code for the new inventory account. #Keeping the old inventory account in the item settings, you clear the item balance from the old inventory account by doing the following: issue all quantity and cost of the item with the issue reason code that you have defined earlier to clear the balance of the old inventory account, and record the balance to the temporary account. #You specify the new inventory account in the settings of the item. #You process a receipt with the item quantity you issued earlier (and at the previously specified cost) with the receipt reason code that you have defined earlier. When you do, the balance is recorded back to the new inventory account and the balance of the temporary account is cleared. #You make sure the temporary account balance is zero, and deactivate the account on the chart of accounts.
After you have performed these steps, the balance is transferred to the new inventory account, and the item is ready for processing additional inventory transactions. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Posting_Classes__Definition_and_Usage|Posting Classes in Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Reason_Codes__Definition_and_Usage|Reason Codes for Inventory] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000])

The majority of transactions with inventory items are performed when the items are purchased or sold, and respective inventory receipts or issues are generated by other documents, such as purchase receipts and sales orders. Because direct inventory transactions (that is, inventory transactions that are not based on any financial documents) are not standard operations, users should specify why the particular inventory transactions were performed.{br}
In this topic, you will read about the creation and use of reason codes in the Inventory module.{br}{TOC} ==Creation of Reason Codes== Before you start configuring the settings of the Inventory module, you must create all necessary reason codes to be used in inventory transactions. You define reason codes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) form. For each reason code, you must specify the following:[anchor|#_16dbe470-3b5a-42f3-8b81-e2bbe2d0ff72] *Identifier: Identifiers of reason codes may have up to 10 characters and can clearly designate the reason of the transaction, as with ''DAMAGE'', ''EXPIRATION'', ''SHRINKAGE'', and ''RETURNS''. *Usage: You specify with what inventory transaction a reason code will be used. You can define reason codes for the following types of inventory transactions: **Receipt **Issue/return **Adjustment **Transfer **Disassembly *General Ledger account: You select the General Ledger account that the system will allocate for transactions with this reason code specified. For details, see [[#_7ff58506-70c6-4157-838e-9c6633966432|General Ledger Accounts for Reason Codes]. *General Ledger subaccount and subaccount mask: If you use subaccounts in Acumatica ERP, you specify the subaccount or the subaccount mask (for a combined subaccount) that the system will use for documents with this reason code specified. For details, see [[#_36b78296-f3a3-4949-aaa5-b88bdb24d742|Subaccounts for Reason Codes]. *Sales account and subaccount: If you create a reason code for issues, you optionally specify a sales account and subaccount for use on sales orders. In addition, the sales account from the reason code can override the sales account in the additional sales transaction that can be generated from an inventory issue. If this ''Issue'' reason code is specified in a sales order, it may override the sales and COGS accounts in the transactions that are then generated from the Accounts Receivable invoice and inventory issue.
After you have created all required reason codes, you can specify default reason codes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. For details, see [[#_1414824c-da76-46ff-9904-bbc42e55a993|Default Reason Codes for Inventory Transactions].{br}{TOC}[anchor|#_7ff58506-70c6-4157-838e-9c6633966432] ==General Ledger Accounts for Reason Codes== Each reason code provides an offset account to be used for the transaction. The type of the offset account depends on the type of transaction for which the reason code is used with as well as the reason for the transaction; in most cases, the offset account is a kind of expense account to record specific costs. For example, reason codes defined for issues are used to provide offset accounts for specific types of issues. If an issue is created to remove expired goods, the offset account can be Expired Goods&rsquo; Costs. An inventory return functions similarly to an issue, with the entries reversed.((({S:Hint}For some sales transactions (which do not refer to any specific sales order type), reason codes may provide a sales account and subaccount because sales subaccounts can be generated only in accordance with the rules specified for the order type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_20_10_00|Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=SO201000|SO201000]) form. )))[anchor|#_36b78296-f3a3-4949-aaa5-b88bdb24d742] ==Subaccounts for Reason Codes== For each reason code, if subaccounts are used in your system, you specify a subaccount and a subaccount mask (which can be used for a combined subaccount). By specifying a subaccount mask, you configure a rule that the system uses to compose a new subaccount identifier by using the segment values of multiple subaccounts. In a combined subaccount of a reason code, you can use segments from the following sources:[anchor|#_92e436f2-b5e8-4ae7-9a5e-aa4c91fe250c] *Inventory item (''I''): The subaccount associated with the item *Warehouse (''W''): The subaccount associated with the warehouse where the transaction is performed *Posting class (''P''): The subaccount associated with the posting class *Reason code (''R''): The subaccount associated with the reason code itself
For example, suppose that a two-segmented subaccount identifier with three characters in each segment is defined. To combine the subaccount segments of a warehouse and inventory item, you use the following mask: <tt>WWW-III</tt>, where <tt>WWW</tt> is the first subaccount segment of a warehouse and <tt>III</tt> is the second subaccount segment of an inventory item. To use a subaccount associated with a reason code, you type the following mask: <tt>RRR-RRR</tt>.{br}
For details on how to use combined subaccounts, see [HelpRoot_Financials\GL__CON_Combined_Subaccounts|Combining Subaccounts].[anchor|#_1414824c-da76-46ff-9904-bbc42e55a993] ==Default Reason Codes for Inventory Transactions== When an inventory document is created directly in the Inventory module, the reason code defines what account will be used as an offset account and what subaccount will mark the transaction. On release of the transaction, the inventory account (which is copied from the stock item) and the offset account (which is copied from the reason code) will be updated with the amount of the transaction. {br}
For each type of inventory transaction, you can specify the default reason code ton the '''General Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. You can assign default reason codes for the following inventory transactions: [anchor|#_66e8af39-269a-4e89-94e7-760ca973fb7b] *Receipts *Issues and returns *Adjustment *Physical inventory adjustments
When you create one of these inventory documents, the system automatically inserts the specified default reason code for the type. Users can replace the default reason code with another reason code defined for the transaction type, if necessary. ((({S:Hint}You specify the default reason code for vendor returns on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_10_10_00|Purchase Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=PO101000|PO101000]) form. For more information on processing vendor returns, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Return_Processing|Purchase Return Processing]. ))) ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Financials\GL__CON_Combined_Subaccounts|Combining Subaccounts] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_GL_Accounts_Inventory|Posting Settings in the Inventory Module] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_20_10_00|Order Types] ([~/?ScreenId=SO201000|SO201000])

Every inventory transaction creates an appropriate posting to the General Ledger module, depending on the particular inventory item, the type of transaction, the warehouse where the item is stocked, and other conditions. A posting class is a required setting for stock items and defines which accounts and subaccounts should be used to post specific transactions to the General Ledger module. Also, posting classes are used to provide the default General Ledger accounts for stock and non-stock items during the initialization of the system or later, when new stock or non-stock items are being added.{br}
In this topic, you will read about posting classes in Acumatica ERP.{br}{TOC} ==Creation of Posting Classes== When the ''Inventory'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can create posting classes by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form.((({S:Hint}Before you start creating posting classes, make sure that all necessary General Ledger accounts and subaccounts have been created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_20_25_00|Chart of Accounts] ([~/?ScreenId=GL202500|GL202500]) form. ))) During the creation of a posting class, you specify the following:[anchor|#_44645ab7-e626-4cdc-83bd-4249426b5fc1] #Class ID: You type a unique identifier that defines the posting class. You can use an alphanumeric string of up to 10 characters as a posting class ID. #General Ledger accounts and subaccounts: You specify the General Ledger accounts and subaccounts assigned to the posting class. The exact set of accounts and subaccounts you need to select depends on the items for which you create a posting class. For details, see [[#_18ccf0fa-9866-4a9f-a0f7-7eff75735bad|General Ledger Accounts and Subaccounts of a Posting Class]. #Posting settings for transactions: You specify which General Ledger account the system must take for which type of transaction, and the rule the system will use to combine subaccounts. For details, see [[#_d03e51b8-f764-437a-b6b5-f50a8c94a2b9|Posting Settings for General Ledger Accounts] and [[#_e87109ba-976e-4b37-b2d4-5d010ecc0523|Posting Settings for GL Subaccounts]. #Reason code for physical inventory: You specify the reason code that the system will use by default for physical inventory involving items associated with this posting class. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Reason_Codes__Definition_and_Usage|Reason Codes for Inventory].
For a procedure, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Posting_Class|To Create a Posting Class].[anchor|#_18ccf0fa-9866-4a9f-a0f7-7eff75735bad] ==General Ledger Accounts and Subaccounts of a Posting Class== You specify the default General Ledger accounts and subaccounts assigned to a posting class on the '''GL Accounts''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form. These default General Ledger accounts and subaccounts simplify data entry on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) and [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) forms. When you assign a posting class to an item class or item, the system copies the General Ledger accounts and subaccounts from the posting class to the item class or item settings.{br}
In the settings of an item class or item, you can override any of the default accounts and subaccounts, if needed.{br}
If you change the posting class for an item class or item, the system updates the General Ledger accounts and subaccounts on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form with the accounts and subaccounts from the new posting class.{br}
For details on General Ledger accounts in inventory, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_GL_Accounts_Inventory|Posting Settings in the Inventory Module].[anchor|#_d03e51b8-f764-437a-b6b5-f50a8c94a2b9] ==Posting Settings for General Ledger Accounts== General Ledger accounts and subaccounts for inventory transactions related to sales, purchases, and valuation of inventory items can be obtained from multiple sources, depending on the business processes established in your organization. On the '''Posting Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form, for each type of account, you specify from which source the system will take this account for the posting class.{br}
In Acumatica ERP, you can select General Ledger accounts from the following sources:[anchor|#_02ef8be6-40c5-469b-805f-f754e07d68b8] *''Inventory item'': The inventory account for all transactions of the item will be the one specified in the item settings regardless of at what warehouse the inventory transaction occurs. *''Warehouse'': The inventory account will vary depending on the warehouse where the inventory transaction is made. You select this source if you use multiple warehouses in the system and each warehouse has a specific inventory account assigned. *''Posting class'': The inventory account assigned to the posting class itself (as specified on the '''GL Accounts''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] form) will be used. You select this source when you need to replace the inventory account that was previously used for items of the posting class with a new account. [anchor|#_e041f519-5f47-40fc-a5e8-03f8f2c03315] ==Basic Scenarios of Posting Class Configuration== When you create posting classes, you can configure the following basic scenarios:[anchor|#_e4a8a151-d9f4-4578-bbd7-35062ab95d9c] *Posting transactions for multiple items to the same General Ledger account: Suppose that you have a single warehouse, and the majority of inventory transactions should be posted to the same General Ledger account. You do the following: **You create a posting class and specify for it the inventory account that the system should use for posting inventory transactions. **You select ''Posting Class'' as the source of the inventory account in the settings of the posting class. **You specify the created posting class in the settings of each item class or inventory item. *Posting transactions to item-specific General Ledger accounts: Suppose that you have particularly valuable items for which you want to allocate specific General Ledger accounts. You do the following: **You specify a separate General Ledger account in the settings of each item class or inventory item that are valuable. **You create a posting class; in its settings, you select ''Inventory Item'' as the source of the inventory account. **You specify the created posting class in the settings of the inventory items that have specific General Ledger accounts. *Posting transactions to warehouse-specific General Ledger accounts: Suppose that you have multiple warehouses and you have separate accounts for each warehouse. You do the following: **You assign an individual inventory account to each warehouse. **You create a posting class and select ''Warehouse'' as the source of the inventory account. **You assign item classes or items to the created posting class.
You can combine basic scenarios to post transactions according to business processes of your organization.[anchor|#_e87109ba-976e-4b37-b2d4-5d010ecc0523] ==Posting Settings for GL Subaccounts== If the ''Subaccounts'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can specify the rules for selecting subaccount segments for inventory transactions that involve items of the posting class. The system can select subaccounts used for transaction posting from the same sources as accounts, but since subaccounts consist of multiple segments, you can combine segment values from different sources to get subaccounts that would reflect all the details of the transaction. For example, if only one inventory account is used in your organization for all inventory items, you might want to provide very specific subaccounts to track which warehouses were involved in every transaction.{br}
On the '''Posting Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form, you can type a subaccount mask that defines how the subaccounts should be composed by using segment values copied from various sources. For each segment, you can select one of the following sources of the segment value:[anchor|#_9d84e026-e754-4580-bd10-ccd74ee08dd9] *Posting class (''P'') *Inventory item (''I'') *Warehouse (''W'')
Consider a simple example of configuring a subaccount mask for a sales subaccount. Suppose there are four segments in the subaccounts used in the system, which have the ''XX-XXX-XX-XX'' format.{br}
If you configure the sales subaccount mask as ''II-III-II-II'', it means that for sales transactions, the sales subaccount from the inventory item will be used.{br}
If you configure the sales subaccount mask as ''WW-PPP-II-PP'', then for sales transactions, the sales subaccount will be a combination of three subaccounts:[anchor|#_98513ca5-26ec-4df8-bb53-6007b2fbc2ba] *The first segment will be copied from the sales subaccount associated with the warehouse. *The second and fourth segments will be copied from the sales subaccount associated with the posting class of the item. *The third segment will be copied from the sales account associated with the inventory item.
For more details on functionality of combined subaccounts, see [HelpRoot_Financials\GL__CON_Combined_Subaccounts|Combining Subaccounts]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Financials\GL__CON_Combined_Subaccounts|Combining Subaccounts] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Reason_Codes__Definition_and_Usage|Reason Codes for Inventory] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_20_25_00|Chart of Accounts] ([~/?ScreenId=GL202500|GL202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_21_10_00|Reason Codes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS211000|CS211000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000])

In Acumatica ERP, you can maintain any number of different units of measure (UOMs) to be used to specify the quantities of products that are purchased, stocked, or sold by your company. In addition, you can specify UOMs of weight and volume to calculate freight costs for third-party carriers. Multiple units of measure are required because items can be sold by the piece or be packed into boxes, packages, crates, and other storage units.{br}
Some units of measure apply to many products and, as such, are defined globally. Other units of measure are used only for particular products or for groups of similar products. In Acumatica ERP, you can define UOMs and conversion rules at all of these levels, as described in the sections below. {br}{TOC} ==Global Units of Measure== You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] ([~/?ScreenId=CS203100|CS203100]) form to define units of measure that can be used globally for all inventory items. You can add new units of measure to the unit conversion reference table on this form and specify how they are converted to units already defined in the table, if applicable. The global UOMs specified in this table can be used throughout Acumatica ERP and are available for selection when a user selects UOMs for a new item class or a base UOM for an item.{br}
You do the following to create an UOM on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] form:[anchor|#_fe12de63-0839-4115-8df9-8025cbde957f] #In the '''From Unit''' and '''To Unit''' columns, you type the unique identifier of the UOM (such as <tt>KG</tt>). #In the '''Multiply/Divide''' column, you keep the default value. #In the '''Conversion Factor''' column, you make sure that the default value, <tt>1.000000</tt>, is specified.
After you create all required UOMs, you can create conversion rules (if necessary) so that the system can calculate prices for items in different UOMs correctly. For more information on conversion rules, see [[#_5b373052-e0d1-414d-86ff-290781b32978|Specification of Conversion Rules] and [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Define_Conversion_Rule_for_UOM|To Define a Conversion Rule for UOMs].{br}
In addition to global UOMs, you can create item-specific UOMs on the fly when you are creating an item class or inventory item. For details, see [[#_5ae07ce8-bb7a-40f6-b083-a9611bca74a9|Default UOMs for Item Classes] and [[#_05db3ae4-d4e4-4a4f-8f78-449c51e0d3bb|Item-Specific UOMs]. ==UOMs of Weight and Volume== If your company uses third-party carriers to deliver sold goods to customers or purchases from vendors, you may need to define UOMs of weight and volume to calculate specific freight amounts. After you have created all required UOMs and conversion rules on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] ([~/?ScreenId=CS203100|CS203100]) form, you can specify global UOMs for weight and volume on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_15_00|Companies] ([~/?ScreenId=CS101500|CS101500]) form. The system will use these UOMs to calculate freight costs.{br}
You can specify weight and volume UOMs for each stock and non-stock item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) and [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) forms, respectively. UOMs specified on these forms have a higher priority than global UOMs specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_15_00|Companies] form.{br}
For information on UOMs used to measure the weight and volume of the items listed on sales orders and purchase receipts, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_BaseWeightVolumeUOMs|Units of Weight and Volume].[anchor|#_5ae07ce8-bb7a-40f6-b083-a9611bca74a9] ==Default UOMs for Item Classes== If the ''Multiple Units of Measure'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, for each item class that is defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form, you can specify the following units to be used by default for items of the class:[anchor|#ul_j3p_zvz_sh] *'''Base Unit''': The unit of measure used to calculate unit costs for items of the class. For stock items, this unit is used for maintaining availability data. Users count the quantities of each stock item at warehouses by using the UOM specified as the base unit for the item. For recommendations on selecting base units, see [[#_6bd9895c-ec51-455b-9f8f-a127161d17ce|Base Unit Selection]. *'''Sales Unit''': The unit of measure typically used when your company sells the item. *'''Purchase Unit''': The unit of measure typically used when your company purchases the item.
If the ''Multiple Units of Measure'' feature is not enabled in your system, you can specify only base units for item classes as well as for individual stock and non-stock items. ((({S:Hint}If you decide later to enable the ''Multiple Units of Measure'' feature, the sales and purchase units for each item class (as well as for each stock and non-stock item) will be assigned the values from the appropriate base units. ))){br}
You can select globally defined units of measure or type a class-specific UOM. Once you have typed a new UOM, a new line with this UOM is added to the conversion tables automatically, so that you can specify how this UOM is converted to the base unit of the class. For detailed instructions, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Define_UOM|To Create an UOM].((({S:Hint}The system will not automatically add class-specific units to the global unit conversion reference table on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] form. ))){br}
The base, sales, and purchase UOMs selected for the class will provide the default values of these settings for items of this class.[anchor|#_05db3ae4-d4e4-4a4f-8f78-449c51e0d3bb] ==Item-Specific UOMs== For particular items of the class, on the '''General Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form, you can select the base, sales, and purchase units. (Boxes for sales and purchase UOMs are displayed only if the ''Multiple Units of Measure'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form.) By default, the system assigns the base, sales, and purchase units of the class to the item. If you need to specify other UOMs, you can select UOMs from the list of globally defined UOMs or type new units. The system will automatically add the new item-specific UOMs to the table of units conversion on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] ([~/?ScreenId=CS203100|CS203100]) form— that is, to the list of globally defined UOMs.((({S:Warn}If you need to change the item&rsquo;s base UOM (or the sales or purchase UOM, if applicable), make sure that the rules for conversion between the current and new UOMs are specified before you use the item with any new UOM in any new transaction. ))) When you enter a transaction and specify the quantity of the inventory item and its unit of measure, the system converts the specified UOM to the base unit for cost-of-sold-goods calculation and to the default sales unit for finding the proper price (or the item&rsquo;s other unit for which the price can be found). ==Cross-Reference Units of Measure== Stock or non-stock items may have alternate IDs specified on the '''Cross-References''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form. You can assign these items UOMs other than the default sales and purchase units of measure to be used when users enter documents with lines in which they enter these alternate IDs. For detailed information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Cross-References#_119e97a3-c747-4cea-a699-ef56e2ead6b5|Using Cross-Reference Units of Measure] in [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Cross-References|Item Cross-References].[anchor|#_6bd9895c-ec51-455b-9f8f-a127161d17ce] ==Base Unit Selection== You may want to select for each item a base unit that is the smallest unit you would ever use when buying or selling the product, so you can avoid any problems caused by rounding. To understand this guideline, consider an example: Suppose that you purchase and stock a product (canned juice) in boxes of 12 cans, and you select a box as the base unit for this product. If you then decided to sell the product by cans, you would need to specify quantities in fractions or define the sales unit (if sales and purchase units are enabled in your system) as 0.0833333 (one-twelfth) of the base unit.{br}
Further imagine that one customer wants to buy 5 cans and another wants to buy another 5 cans. In both cases, the sales order would specify 0.417 units (5 &#42; 0.0833333), and each customer would get 5 cans. However, the remaining 0.166 units don&rsquo;t actually equate to the 2 cans left in the box. During a financial period, in a warehouse, these rounding problems could cause a significant discrepancy between the quantities on books and the physical quantities.{br}
During physical inventory, counting is performed in base units, so if the base unit for the product is not the smallest UOM applicable to the item, counting results may prove incorrect. Considering the above example, counting only boxes can result in incorrect total number of cans because some of the boxes may not be full. Thus, we recommend using a base unit that is the smallest unit your company uses when buying and selling the product.[anchor|#_5b373052-e0d1-414d-86ff-290781b32978] ==Specification of Conversion Rules== When you define conversion rules for UOMs, make sure that the decimal precision specified in the '''Quantity Decimal Places''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_15_00|Companies] ([~/?ScreenId=CS101500|CS101500]) form does not cut off any meaningful digits.{br}
If different UOMs are used as base, sales, and purchase units, you specify conversion rules with respect to the UOM selected as the base unit for the item. For instance, suppose an item is sold to customers by the piece (''PIECE''), making ''PIECE'' its sales unit. The product is stocked in boxes, and each box (''BOX'') includes 16 pieces. The product is purchased from a vendor in containers. Each container (''CONTAINER'') contains 20 boxes, and the purchase unit is ''CONTAINER''. As the base unit, you can select ''PIECE'' or ''BOX''. (The smallest unit is usually selected, for reasons described in the previous section.) If you selected ''PIECE'', you would specify the following conversion rules.[anchor|#table_e33_v35_tv] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="25%" ! From Unit !width="25%" ! Multiply/Divide !width="25%" ! Conversion Factor !width="25%" ! To Unit |- | ''CONTAINER'' | ''Multiply'' | <tt>320</tt> | ''PIECE'' |- | ''BOX'' | ''Multiply'' | <tt>16</tt> | ''PIECE'' |} Notice that the specified conversion rules are not reversible—the system cannot use the rule in the first row of the above table to recalculate the quantity specified in pieces to the quantity specified in containers.{br}
Also, any conversion should be specified directly with respect to the base UOM, and it would be impossible to convert any quantity specified in containers to the quantity specified in boxes if you specify the rules as follows.[anchor|#table_dtm_dn5_tv] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="25%" ! From Unit !width="25%" ! Multiply/Divide !width="25%" ! Conversion Factor !width="25%" ! To Unit |- | ''CONTAINER'' | ''Multiply'' | <tt>20</tt> | '' BOX'' |- | ''BOX'' | ''Multiply'' | <tt>16</tt> | ''PIECE'' |} If you decide to use ''BOX'' as the base unit, you must define the rules differently, as follows.[anchor|#table_yxn_dj5_tv] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="25%" ! From Unit !width="25%" ! Multiply/Divide !width="25%" ! Conversion Factor !width="25%" ! To Unit |- | ''CONTAINER'' | ''Multiply'' | <tt>20</tt> | ''BOX'' |- | ''PIECE'' | ''Divide'' | <tt>16</tt> | ''BOX'' |} ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Define_UOM|To Create an UOM] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_BaseWeightVolumeUOMs|Units of Weight and Volume] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] ([~/?ScreenId=CS203100|CS203100])

When a carrier is used to deliver products from your organization to a customer, the carrier can charge your company specific freight amounts that depend on the weights or volumes of the packages in shipments. The carrier may also set restrictions on the weight or volume of packages. Landed costs incurred for shipments delivered from vendors to your company can be calculated by the weight or volume of the items in the shipment.{br}

In Acumatica ERP, you can select the base units of measure (UOMs) for weight and volume and set up the automatic calculation of weights and volumes for sales and purchase orders. In this topic, you will read about weight and volume UOMs.{br}{TOC}
==The Base Weight and Volume UOMs==
You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_15_00|Companies] ([~/?ScreenId=CS101500|CS101500]) form to specify the base UOMs for weight and volume.{br}

On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] ([~/?ScreenId=CS203100|CS203100]) form, you should first create a unit of measure (UOM) to be used in your system as the base UOM for weight. The weights of all sales and purchase orders will be calculated in this UOM. However, if the items differ in weight significantly, you can create other UOMs for measuring the weights of the base units of stock and non-stock items. For each additional weight UOM, you must specify the rules for converting this UOM to the base weight UOM. {br}

For example, suppose that you need to create weight UOMs for a gram (''GRAM'') and pound (''LB'') and define conversion rules to convert the weights measured in pounds to weights measured in grams and to convert the weights measured in grams to weights measured in pounds. On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] form, you would do the following:[anchor|#_a5ab2ac2-b52c-47ce-9003-5f196a10952f]
#Create the <tt>GRAM</tt> UOM for grams.
#Create the <tt>LB</tt> UOM for pounds.
#Create a conversion rule from grams to pounds with the ''Multiply'' conversion type and <tt>453.5923</tt> conversion factor
#Create a conversion rules from pounds to grams with the ''Multiply'' conversion type and <tt>0.0022046</tt> conversion factor
#:((({S:Hint}Here you specify the conversion factor as 0.0022046 with 7 decimal places. This value shows how many pounds one gram contains. In your system, the decimal precision is defined in the '''Quantity Decimal Places''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_15_00|Companies] ([~/?ScreenId=CS101500|CS101500]) form. Make sure that the selected decimal precision does not cut off any meaningful digits. For instance, if you set the number of decimal places for quantities to 2, this would result in incorrect conversions from grams to pounds.
)))

For a general procedure that describes how to create UOMs and conversion rules, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Define_UOM|To Create an UOM].{br}

On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] form, you should define a UOM that will be used in your system to measure the volume of specific quantities of the items listed on sales and purchase orders. You should also define all other UOMs that may be used to measure the volumes that the base units of various items can take and specify the conversion factors with respect to the base volume UOM.{br}

On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form, select the base weight UOM in the '''Weight UOM''' box and select the base volume UOM in the '''Volume UOM''' box.
==Weight and Volume of Stock Items==
For each stock item, you can specify the weight and the volume (measured in a specific volume UOM) of its base unit on the '''Packaging''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. For non-stock items, you can specify these values (if applicable) by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form.{br}

For the item-specific weight and volume UOMs, you must specify rules for conversion to the appropriate base UOMs either on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form or on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_31_00|Units of Measure] ([~/?ScreenId=CS203100|CS203100]) form.{br}

If the ''Multiple Units of Measure'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, make sure that rules for converting each sales and purchase unit to the base UOM selected for the item are defined in the system. Also, if the '''Use a Price Adjustment Multiplier''' check box is selected on the '''General Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000]) form, you can specify a price adjustment multiplier for the item. For more information on adjusting prices, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Units_of_Measure_and_Conversions|Units of Measure and Conversions].
==Weight and Volume Calculation for Purchase Receipts==
The system can calculate the weight and volume of the received quantities of stock and non-stock items for each purchase receipt.{br}

The landed cost specified for each purchase receipt can be split among the items listed in the receipt in proportion to the item weights or volumes (among other options). For more information, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\PO__con_Landed_Cost_Tracking|Processing Landed Cost Documents].
