In Acumatica ERP, you can create item classes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form to group stock or non-stock items with similar properties and to provide default settings for new items.{br}
Users specify an item class when they create a new stock or non-stock item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form, and the system fills in many values, thus saving users time and increasing the accuracy of the entered data. Some of these default values can be overridden for individual items, if needed. The item class is a required setting for a stock item.{br}
For details about how to create an item class, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Item_Class|To Create an Item Class].{br}
In this topic, you will read about item classes in Acumatica ERP.{br}{TOC} ==Item Class Settings== Each item class can specify the following:[anchor|#_65212b60-1b91-4af1-b2da-e30cd724a24a] *Whether the class groups stock items, for which the system generates inventory transactions, or non-stock items, which is not tracked in inventory. *The default settings that the item class provides to items of the class and that you can change later by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form. For details, see [[#_9e658006-b406-451d-bed2-ad6ea6d0aca4|Default Settings for Inventory Items]. *The availability calculation rule that applies to the items of the item class that groups stock items. For details, see [[#_e3f04e17-91c0-4160-a1be-25b242edf1bf|Availability Calculation Rules in an Item Class]. *The hierarchy of item classes. For details, see [[#_532af870-0e27-493b-b357-517cac9257fa|Hierarchy of Item Classes]. *The method of demand calculation for replenishment of items that are grouped by the item class. For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Automated_Replenishment|Automated Replenishment]. *The configuration of custom attributes that items might have, such as color and size. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Item_Attributes|Inventory Item Attributes].
You can specify default item classes in the '''Default Stock Item Class''' and '''Default Non-Stock Item Class''' boxes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. The system will copy the settings of the default item class to newly created stock and non-stock item classes.[anchor|#_9e658006-b406-451d-bed2-ad6ea6d0aca4] ==Default Settings for Inventory Items== The default settings that an item class provides to inventory items are the following:[anchor|#_99dba38b-2c3c-4943-a520-f4600d13ea2a] *Item type (these types are different for stock and non-stock items) *Valuation method *Tax category *Posting class *Lot or serial number *Default warehouse *Units of measure *Custom attributes *Replenishment class
You can plan item classes so that they aggregate as much information as possible about the groups of similar inventory items, including the posting classes. After you configure the item classes in this way, you will have to specify a minimum of information for individual inventory items during manual data entry or import—for example, only '''Inventory ID''', '''Description''', and '''Item Class'''—while the rest of the information will be automatically populated based on the selected item class.[anchor|#_e3f04e17-91c0-4160-a1be-25b242edf1bf] ==Availability Calculation Rules in an Item Class== The system tracks the on-hand quantity of items in inventory and calculates the available quantity of items, which can be used for inventory planning and replenishment. You might want to include anticipated goods in the available quantity, which you can specify in the availability calculation settings. The availability calculation rule is defined at the item class level and cannot be changed for particular items. For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Availability_Calculation|Availability Calculation].[anchor|#_532af870-0e27-493b-b357-517cac9257fa] ==Hierarchy of Item Classes== You can configure the ''INITEMCLASS'' segmented key so that it has multiple segments, each denoting a level of item class hierarchy. Then you can define the hierarchy of item classes and use item classes for categorizing items.{br}
To use item classes for categorizing items, you can set the hierarchy of the item classes directly in the item class IDs. For example, suppose that your organization sells electronics and computers. You can create an item class for computers and include child item classes for laptops, monitors, and keyboards in this item class. Similarly, you can create an item class for electronics with item classes for audio players, speakers, and headphones included. For details on hierarchical item classes, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Hierarchy_of_Item_Classes|Hierarchy of Item Classes ]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Availability_Calculation|Availability Calculation] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Automated_Replenishment|Automated Replenishment] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Hierarchy_of_Item_Classes|Hierarchy of Item Classes ] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Items|Inventory Items] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Non-Stock_Item_Support|Non-Stock Items in the Inventory Module] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500])

In Acumatica ERP, stock items are usually physical goods (such as computers, cell phones, cables, and auto parts) that you purchase or manufacture and sell to your customers. Stock items may have lot or serial numbers you can use to track the items in your system. You can create stock items by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form only if the ''Inventory'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form.{br}
In this topic, you can find information about stock items in Acumatica ERP.{br}{TOC} ==Configuration of Stock Items== You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form to create stock items in the system. You must create a stock item for each good that you purchase or sell and that you want to track in the Inventory module. To create a stock item, you do the following:[anchor|#_dc7196d4-851c-41c7-877a-7575b5248702] #You type a unique inventory ID for the item. For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Items#_38038e84-0869-4440-b1d5-5f91ce3f2719|Inventory IDs] in [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Items|Inventory Items]. #You select one of the existing item classes, which will provide default settings to the item, such as item type, valuation method, tax category, posting class, default warehouse, availability calculation rules, units of measure and replenishment settings. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Classes|Item Classes]. #Optional: You change any of the settings provided by the selected item class as needed. #Optional: If you use multiple warehouse locations, you select locations for issue and receipt for the stock item you are configuring. For more information on warehouse locations, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Warehouse_Locations|Warehouse Locations]. #Optional: If you use third-party carriers to deliver the stock item, you specify the weight or volume of the item and select a packaging option. For details, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_Automated_Shipments|Automatic Packaging for Integrated Carriers].
For details about how to create a stock item, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Stock_Item|To Create a Stock Item]. ==Types of Stock Items== You select one of the following stock item types, which are used for informational purposes only and designate the inventories that a company may have, for each stock item:[anchor|#ul_kxz_55f_wr] *''Finished Good'': You use this type for finished goods that you sell to customers. *''Component Part'': You can use this type for component items from which intermediate assemblies and finished goods are produced during kit assembly processes. *''Subassembly'': You can use this type for intermediate assemblies from which finished goods are produced during kit assembly processes.
==Transactions with Stock Items== After you have created stock items in the system and configured their settings, you can start processing transactions. Unlike with non-stock items, transactions with stock items need to be processed starting from the forms of the Purchase Orders or Sales Orders module, such as [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_10_00|Purchase Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=PO301000|PO301000]) form. From these modules, the system generates the proper inventory transactions and the corresponding Accounts Payable and Accounts Receivable documents.{br}
Stock items cannot be manually selected in Accounts Receivable invoices. In Accounts Payable bills, you can select stock items; however, the Accounts Payable documents can be released only after all lines with stock items are linked to the corresponding lines of the purchase receipts that have been released in the Purchase Orders module.((({S:Hint}You cannot delete a stock item in the system if there are any completed transactions with the item, any unreleased documents that includes this item, or any nonzero quantity of the item at any warehouse location. ))) ==Stock Item Tracking== The system automatically tracks stock items and maintains availability data: how many base units are on hand, how many are ordered from vendors, and how many are booked to sales orders and shipments. You can configure how exactly the availability data is computed, and the data is updated as the item is received, invoiced, adjusted, or transferred. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Availability_Calculation|Availability Calculation].{br}
Stock items are also tracked by their cost value. Various valuation methods are available for tracking item costs (for details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods]). Typically, a stock item is an asset until it is sold. Its cost becomes an expense.{br}
The system also automatically monitors when the stock level of the item falls below the defined minimum and automatically calculates the quantities required to replenish the stock, based on the demand for the item and the inventory information you have defined for the stock item. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Automated_Replenishment|Automated Replenishment]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Items|Inventory Items] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Classes|Item Classes] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Availability_Calculation|Availability Calculation] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Automated_Replenishment|Automated Replenishment] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000])

Non-stock items, which are defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form, may be "products" that are not physical entities and thus cannot be stocked in warehouses. Many organizations sell items that can’t be found on their shelves, such as product warranties, or services such as product assembly, installation, or customization.{br}
Whereas some items are obviously non-stock, such as labor rates and services, other items that are physical entities (such as gift-wrapping) can be either stock or non-stock. The decision about whether to consider physical entities stock or non-stock depends on the company&rsquo;s inventory policies and other conditions.{br}
In the system, non-stock items are handled differently from stock items that are kept in warehouses (and tracked accordingly). For stock items, the system maintains all cost, quantity, sales, and cost-of-goods-sold information. Because non-stock items do not require the tracking of quantities, the system maintains only standard costs and base price information for them.((({S:Hint}If the ''Inventory and Order Management'' group of features is not included in your Acumatica ERP license, you will be able to create non-stock items and use them in the Accounts Receivable and Accounts Payable documents. However, you will not be able to define posting classes for them or to update their prices and costs in bulk. If the ''Inventory and Order Management'' group of features is enabled but the ''Inventory'' feature is not enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can still use non-stock items in sales orders, purchase orders, and purchase requisitions with some limitations. (Some elements you use for non-stock items, such as the '''Require Receipt''' and '''Require Shipment''' boxes, are unavailable. For more information about settings that depend on this feature, see the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form reference.) ))){br}{TOC} ==Types of Non-Stock Items== Acumatica ERP supports the following types of non-stock items, one of which can be selected in the '''Type''' box of the '''General Settings '''tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form: *''Non-Stock Item'': A general type of a non-stock item. You can use it for any unspecific type of non-physical items or for physical items that you don&rsquo;t need to register in inventory. *''Labor'' or ''Labor Item'': A non-stock item mostly used as a source of General Ledger accounts for recording sales of labor. *''Service'': A non-stock item to designate service fees. *''Charge'': A non-stock item that represents charges of a specific type. *''Expense'': A non-stock item that represents expenses of a specific type.
On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form, you can create item classes for non-stock items to provide default settings for each type of non-stock item used in your business. With these classes defined, users can specify an item class when they use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form to define a new non-stock item, and the system fills in common values, thus saving time and increasing accuracy. ==Settings for Non-Stock Items== Information about non-stock items and their properties is maintained on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form, which is available in the Accounts Receivable, Accounts Payable, and Inventory modules. The list below describes some of the settings you can provide for a non-stock item by using this form: *Inventory ID: Every non-stock item is assigned an unique identifier based on the ''INVENTORY'' segmented key. For details on the ways the identifier can be configured, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Items|Inventory Items]. For material non-stock items, you can specify a default warehouse and specify whether the items require shipping and receipts on purchase. *:((({S:Hint}If subitems are used in your system, they do not apply to non-stock items. ))) *Units of measure and conversion rules: For each non-stock item, you can select the units of measure (UOMs) used as base, sales, and purchase units for the item and specify conversion rules for them and for other UOMs used for the item. You can select UOMs from the list of those available for the item class or enter new UOMs on the fly. Every conversion rule is specified with respect to the UOM selected as the item&rsquo;s base unit. *Packaging options: If the non-stock item requires shipping, specify the weight of the base unit and the UOM used to measure the weight. *General Ledger accounts and subaccounts (if subaccounts are applicable in your system): Purchases and sales of non-stock items do not affect companies&rsquo; assets, so the General Ledger accounts and subaccounts used for non-stock items are limited to sales accounts, expense accounts, and accounts required for posting transactions related to kit assembly if the item is a kit or a kit component. You can use subaccounts to detail records within each account. *:((({S:Hint}If a receipt is required for a non-stock item, a price variance account and a purchase accrual account must be specified to record purchases of this non-stock item. When the receipt is matched to the invoice, any price variance for the non-stock item is recorded to the specified price variance account. ))) *Posting class: If the ''Inventory'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can create posting classes to provide default sales or expense accounts and subaccounts for non-stock items. If no posting class is specified for a non-stock item, the default expense subaccount is generated according to the rule specified in the '''Combine Expense Sub. From''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_10_10_00|Accounts Payable Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AP101000|AP101000]) form and the default sales subaccount is specified in the '''Combine Sales Sub. From''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_10_10_00|Accounts Receivable Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=AR101000|AR101000]) form. *Price information: For non-stock items of all types, you can specify price classes and assign prices that become effective on specific dates. ((({S:Hint}Only the standard cost valuation method applies to non-stock items. ))) ==Non-Stock Item Costs== Non-stock items do not affect the company&rsquo;s inventory balance. However, to make it possible to enter the non-stock item cost and use it in the non-stock item price calculation, you can maintain standard costs for non-stock items.{br}
The standard costs are determined outside of the system, and the values should include some of the indirect and direct costs allocated. You can specify the standard cost for a non-stock item as a pending cost on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form. Along with the pending cost, you can specify a date when the cost will become effective. Standard costs are defined with respect to the base unit of the stock item. {br}
If you want to update standard costs for non-stock items, use the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form. You enter a pending cost and the date for the new cost and then click '''Actions &gt; Update Cost''' on the form toolbar. The system displays only the last cost and the current cost. The historical costs that were effective before the last cost are not stored in the database.{br}
If you want to make similar changes to many or all non-stock (and possibly stock) items, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_20_00|Update Standard Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=IN502000|IN502000]) form. On this form, you can enter new costs and compare current and pending costs side by side for all items that you select. If you are satisfied with the changes, you can update the current standard costs with the pending standard costs for all items or only selected ones. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods]. ==Prices for Non-Stock Items== You can enter default prices for non-stock items individually by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form and update the prices any time. Default prices have no expiration dates and cannot be specified as based on the items' quantities. For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Base_Prices|Default Prices]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_IDs_and_Subitem_Codes|Inventory Subitems] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Accounting_for_Kits|Inventory Item Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Items|Inventory Items] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Item_Attributes|Inventory Item Attributes] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Base_Prices|Default Prices] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_20_00|Update Standard Costs] ([~/?ScreenId=IN502000|IN502000])

An organization that distributes goods may have many items in stock. In this case, users who work with inventory items in the system may have specific tasks and work with only particular item classes. When users create a sales order, they need to enter an inventory ID for each product. You can define restriction groups to limit the lists of inventory items particular users see.{br}
In this topic, you will read about managing the visibility of inventory items to users in the system.[anchor|#_89329bcb-f0e7-4c6a-a023-c2f87248120e]((({S:Hint}In Acumatica ERP, you can configure groups with direct and inverse restriction. In this topic, for simplicity, groups with direct restriction are used in examples. You can use inverse restriction groups in the same way as you use direct restriction groups. For details on the types of restriction groups, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Types_of_Restriction_Groups|Types of Restriction Groups]. ))){br}{TOC} ==Visibility of Inventory Items to Users== The list of inventory items from which employees should select an item can be very long, which increases the probability of an entry error. By using restriction groups, you can reduce the list of inventory items that users see on forms. For more information about restriction groups, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Overview_of_Restriction_Groups|Restriction Groups in Acumatica ERP].{br}
For example, suppose that your organization sells furniture, and that each sales manager works with furniture for a particular room, such as kitchen, living room, and bedroom. When managers create a sales order, they should select items from only the list of furniture they sell to avoid entry mistakes. Further suppose that User K sells kitchen furniture, User L sells living room furniture, and User M sells bedroom furniture. To restrict the visibility of inventory items to the appropriate users in the system, you would create the following restriction groups with direct restriction on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_30_00|Inventory Item Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN103000|IN103000]) form:[anchor|#_a9365235-5aa9-40ee-bb79-3221390f1298] #Group K: In this group, include User K and all inventory IDs for kitchen furniture items. #Group L: To this group, add User L and all inventory IDs for items of living room furniture. #Group M: In this group, include User M and all inventory IDs for bedroom furniture items.
As a result, the visibility of the inventory items in sales orders will be restricted in the system as follows:[anchor|#_23b94234-7018-4398-a0f4-f3c82021b1ae] *User K can view and select only inventory items for kitchen furniture. *User L can work with only inventory items for living room furniture. *User M can see and select only inventory items for bedroom furniture. *Other users cannot see the inventory items that have been added to the three restriction groups in the system.
==Forms for Inventory Item Security== In the following table, you can find the list of the forms that you can use to manage restriction groups with inventory items and the tasks that you can perform by using each form.[anchor|#_745cfbb0-e124-4e4a-86b4-3c207b3943e4] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="50%" ! Task !width="50%" ! Form |- | To initially configure the visibility of an inventory item to users | [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_30_00|Inventory Item Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN103000|IN103000]) |- | To change the visibility of an inventory item in multiple restriction groups | [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_30_20|Restriction Groups by Item] ([~/?ScreenId=IN103020|IN103020]) |- | To change the visibility of inventory items to a user in multiple restriction groups | [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_35|Restriction Groups by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201035|SM201035]) |}[anchor|#_b193d503-fb3d-4eae-a82c-d293fb5a35ff] For information about how to add or remove objects from a restriction group, see [HelpRoot_Administration\RS__con_Operations_Restriction_Groups|Operations with Restriction Groups]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Overview_of_Restriction_Groups|Restriction Groups in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Types_of_Restriction_Groups|Types of Restriction Groups] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_30_00|Inventory Item Access] ([~/?ScreenId=IN103000|IN103000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_30_20|Restriction Groups by Item] ([~/?ScreenId=IN103020|IN103020]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_35|Restriction Groups by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201035|SM201035])

You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form to create non-stock items you want to track in the system.{br}
This topic describes how to create a non-stock item for inventory with basic settings—that is, when the ''Inventory'' feature is enabled under the ''Standard Inventory'' group of features and the ''Advanced Inventory'' feature is disabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form.[anchor|#_7b3c70f0-3313-4751-8a2f-aaeb7345a049]((({S:Hint}To open any form, you can navigate to it or search for it (by its name or by its form ID without periods). For more information about search capabilities, see [HelpRoot_Interface\UIG__con_New_UI_Search|Search in the Modern UI]. ))) ==Before You Proceed==[anchor|#_dd05007f-62ea-459d-9882-e70769310176] *Optional: If you use item classes for non-stock items, make sure that you have created an item class that provides default settings for the item you are creating. *If you do not use item classes, make sure that the posting class, the tax category, and the units of measure that you want to use for the item have been created in the system.
==To Create a Non-Stock Item for Inventory==[anchor|#_dddfe74a-2d89-43af-9646-6a9c3427d7a6] #Open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form by searching for or navigating to it. #In the '''Inventory ID''' box, type the unique identifier of the item. #In the '''Description''' box, type a description of the item that will help users identify it. #Optional: In the '''Item Class''' box of the '''Item Defaults''' section on the '''General Settings''' tab, select the item class to be used to provide default settings. #:Make sure that the default settings copied from the item class are applicable to the non-stock item. If not, specify new values for settings, as needed. #If you have not specified an item class, on the '''General Settings''' tab, do the following : ##In the '''Posting Class''' box of the '''Item Defaults''' section, specify the posting class to provide posting settings for the item. ##In the '''Tax Category''' box, specify the tax category to be applied to the item. ##In the '''Base Unit''' box of the '''Unit of Measure''' section, specify the base unit of measure for the item. #Optional: On the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab, specify the settings to calculate cost and price for the non-stock item. #On the form toolbar, click '''Save''' to save your changes.

If your organization sells not only individual inventory items but also bundles of stock or non-stock items to its customers, you can treat these bundles as single items referred to as ''inventory kits'' in Acumatica ERP.{br}
In this chapter, you will find information about kit types and the configuration and management of kits. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#_a06d44bb-4481-4cc2-a284-40d71010e11b] {| class="checklist invisiblechecklist" | width="100%" |- | [anchor|#_80954e07-d91f-4ed5-9dc6-6a4343369b51] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Accounting_for_Kits|Inventory Item Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Stock_Kits|Stock Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Non_Stock_Kits|Non-Stock Kits]
| [anchor|#_d9dbdceb-0db0-4715-b399-98b1a079a1c3] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Stock_Kit|To Create a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Add_Revision_to_Stock_Kit|To Add a Revision to a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Assemble_Stock_Kit|To Assemble a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Disassemble_Stock_Kit|To Disassemble a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Non_Stock_Kit|To Create a Non-Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Non_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Non-Stock Kit]
|}

A kit is a bundle of stock and non-stock items that increases the value of the kit components. In Acumatica ERP, you can use kits of inventory items if your organization sells multiple inventory items together and wants to track these items as a whole. For example, suppose that an organization sells cheese and wine and also offers nicely packed baskets with a bottle of wine and a set of cheese that pairs well with this wine. To track these baskets in the Inventory module, the organization uses kits, which include a bottle of wine, several cheeses, and a basket as stock items, and the delivery service and packaging as non-stock items.((({S:Hint}To use the kit functionality, make sure the ''Kit Assembly'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. ))) In this topic, you will read about kit types and revisions of kit specifications.{br}{TOC} ==Kit Types== You can create stock and non-stock kits. The main difference between these kit types is that the system tracks stock kits in inventory and does not track non-stock kits. The table below compares stock and non-stock kits.[anchor|#table_yfs_ffm_qy] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- ! !Stock Kit !Non-Stock Kit |- | colspan="3" | '''Components''' |- | Stock components | Yes | Yes |- | Non-stock components | Yes | Yes |- | Kit specification revisions | Multiple | One |- | Issue of components of s stock kit | When a kit is assembled | When a kit is issued |- | Expense accrual for non-stock components | When a kit is assembled | Not applicable |- | Lot- or serial-numbered components | Serial-numbered components can be used only in serial-numbered kits | Yes, except for components with the ''When-Used'' assignment method or the ''User-Enterable'' issue method |- | colspan="3" | '''Kit units''' (single entities of a kit) |- | Production/disassembly transactions | Required | Not applicable |- | Inventory tracking | Yes, as a regular stock item; stock components do not exist in inventory after the kit is assembled | No; stock components are tracked individually |- | Inventory value | Value of the kit unit received to inventory upon production | Values of its stock components |- | Availability tracking | Yes | No |- | Receipt of a kit unit | On kit production transaction | Not applicable |- | Issue of a kit unit | Inventory issue of the kit unit | Inventory issue of stock component units |- | Lot/serial tracking of kit units | Applicable | Not applicable |- | Disassembly revision | The revision used for assembly of a serial-tracked kit, and any revision of a non-serial-tracked kit | Not applicable |- | Sales return options | A kit unit | A kit unit or any kit components |- | Sales return revision | Not applicable | The current revision of the kit |} For detailed information on kits, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Stock_Kits|Stock Kits] and [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Non_Stock_Kits|Non-Stock Kits]. ==Kit Revisions== To represent kits in the system, you create specifications, which define the stock and non-stock items included in a kit, by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500]) form. Each specification has at least one ''revision'', which is automatically created when you create a specification. A revision is a version of the same kit, which has minor differences from the previous version. For example, suppose that your organization sells computers and offers a keyboard, a mouse, a leather case, and software installation service as a kit. If you change the vendor of leather cases, you can just change the inventory item for the case in the kit and instead of creating a new kit.{br}
For stock kits, you can create multiple revisions of the same specification. When you assemble a stock kit, you can use only the latest revision. If you need to disassemble a stock kit, you select the revision that was used for kit assembly.{br}
For non-stock kits, only one revision is created when you create a specification by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] form. You cannot add multiple revisions, as for stock kits.{br}
For each stock or non-stock kit revision, you can allow users to add components to the kit during assembly by selecting the '''Allow Component Addition''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] form and to change the quantity of components in the kit by selecting the '''Allow Component Qty. Variance''' check box for each kit component. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Non_Stock_Kits|Non-Stock Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Stock_Kits|Stock Kits] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500])

A stock kit is a bundle of stock and non-stock components. You create each kit and add it to inventory by processing a production transaction. The kit production subtracts the stock components from inventory and adds the kit units to inventory instead. After you have assembled a kit, you can disassemble it back to its components. When a stock kit is sold, one line item appears in the transaction, and the on-hand quantity of the kit is reduced.{br}
In this topic, you will find details about the configuration, assembly, disassembly, and cost calculation of stock kits.{br}{TOC} ==Configuration of Stock Kits== You do the following to configure a stock kit:[anchor|#_63d4a36d-6746-432c-b903-67587431857f] #You create item classes for kits with similar settings by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Item_Class|To Create an Item Class]. #You create as many kits as you need by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. To indicate that each item is a kit, you select the '''Is a Kit''' check box on the '''General Settings''' tab of this form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Stock_Kit|To Create a Stock Kit]. #You create a specification for each kit by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500]) form. In the specification, you select the inventory items that will be included in the kit and specify the settings of each component. Any lot- and serial-tracked stock items can be added to the specification of a stock kit. For details on this step, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Stock Kit]. #You create and release a kit assembly document by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] ([~/?ScreenId=IN307000|IN307000]) form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Assemble_Stock_Kit|To Assemble a Stock Kit]. #You assign sales prices to kits as follows: #*If you sell a limited number of kits, you assign the default prices on a per-kit basis by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form. #*If you are selling more than ten kits, you assign multiple sales prices to kits by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_10|Sales Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202010|AR202010]) form.
A stock kit may require a serial or lot number and an expiration date to be assigned when the kit is produced or sold, depending on the item class settings. For details on lot and serial numbers, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Lot_and_Serial_Numbers|Lot and Serial Numbers].{br}
You can disassemble a stock kit at any time. You may want to do this, for example, when its expiration date has approached. ==Assembly and Disassembly of Stock Kits== You must assemble a stock kit by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] ([~/?ScreenId=IN307000|IN307000]) form before you add the kit to a sales order. The kit assembly document lists the components with their quantities and costs, as determined by the kit specification. Each time a stock kit is assembled and its kit assembly document is released, the on-hand quantities of the items used as components are automatically decreased, and the on-hand quantity of the kits is increased. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Assemble_Stock_Kit|To Assemble a Stock Kit].{br}
On assembly of stock kits, the standard costs of the kit&rsquo;s non-stock components are recorded to the Expense Accrual accounts specified by the '''Use Inventory/Accrual Account From''' setting of the posting class (on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form) of each of the non-stock components.{br}
If disassembly might be required for a stock kit (for example, because of an expiration date), it can be performed in accordance with the revision used to assemble the kit. You can create and release a disassembly document with the ''Disassembly'' operation selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] form. The quantity of components extracted from the kit is estimated using the disassembly coefficient specified for each stock component. However, the quantities of stock components and non-stock components are not validated in any way, and you can manually adjust the calculated quantities.{br}
For details about how to disassemble a stock kit, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Disassemble_Stock_Kit|To Disassemble a Stock Kit]. ==Cost Calculation For Stock Kits== The assembly of stock kits (with valuation methods other than the standard cost method) creates a new cost layer. The cost of a stock kit is calculated based on the costs of components when the document is released. The total cost of the kit is the total cost of stock components according to the specification&rsquo;s revision, the cost of components added during assembly, and the rates of non-stock components of the ''Labor'' and ''Service'' types multiplied by their quantities.{br}
If the standard cost method is used for the stock kit, any difference between the currently effective standard cost and the total cost of components is recorded (as with non-stock kits) to the Standard Cost Variance account determined by the posting class of the stock kit.{br}
When a stock kit is disassembled, the costs of its stock components, which are returned to inventory, are calculated depending on the valuation method of the components as follows:[anchor|#ul_txg_lkh_yx] *''Average'': The cost of the component is calculated based on the setting of the '''Avg. Default Returns Cost''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000]) form. By default, this setting is the average cost of the item at the warehouse. You can also select the last cost as the value of this box. *''FIFO'': The cost of the component is calculated based on the setting of the '''FIFO Default Returns Cost''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] form. By default, this setting is the average cost of the item at the warehouse. You can also select the last cost as the value of this box. *''Specific'': The cost of the component is the average cost of the item at the warehouse. If there is no average cost of the item at the warehouse, the last cost of the item at the warehouse is used. *''Standard'': The cost of the component is the standard cost of the item at the warehouse, if any standard cost is defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) form. Otherwise, the global standard cost of the item defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form is used.
==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Accounting_for_Kits|Inventory Item Kits] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Assemble_Stock_Kit|To Assemble a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Stock_Kit|To Create a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Disassemble_Stock_Kit|To Disassemble a Stock Kit] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_45_00|Item Warehouse Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204500|IN204500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_70_00|Kit Assembly] ([~/?ScreenId=IN307000|IN307000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_10|Sales Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202010|AR202010]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_40_00|Warehouses] ([~/?ScreenId=IN204000|IN204000])

A non-stock kit is a bundle of stock and non-stock components; you assign an individual inventory identifier to the non-stock kit, and it can be selected in sales orders. Non-stock kits are virtual kits because they neither produced nor tracked in inventory, unlike stock kits. The stock components of the non-stock kit remain in inventory and can be sold in the kit or as separate units.{br}
In this topic, you will read about the configuration, processing, and cost calculation of non-stock kits.{br}{TOC}[anchor|#nonstockkits] ==Configuration of Non-Stock Kits== When you create a non-stock kit, you do the following:[anchor|#_a8651c20-e547-4259-8087-5559ccb78e43] #If you need to create a number of kits with similar settings, you create an item class for each group of kits by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Item_Class|To Create an Item Class]. #You create as many kits as you need by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form. To indicate that an item is a kit, you select the '''Is a Kit''' check box on the '''General Settings''' tab of this form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Non_Stock_Kit|To Create a Non-Stock Kit]. #You create a specification for each kit by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500]) form. In the specification, you select the inventory items that will be included in the kit and specify the settings of each component. Any lot- and serial-tracked stock items can be added to the specification of a non-stock kit, except for items with the ''When Used'' assignment method or with the ''User-Enterable'' issue method specified for their lot/serial classes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000]) form. For details on this step, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Specification_for_Non_Stock_Kit|To Create a Specification for a Non-Stock Kit]. #You assign sales prices to kits as follows: #*If you sell a limited number of kits, you assign the default prices on a per-kit basis by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] form. #*If you are selling more than ten kits, you assign multiple sales prices to kits by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_20_20_10|Sales Price Worksheets] ([~/?ScreenId=AR202010|AR202010]) form.
==Processing of Non-Stock Kits == As with non-stock items, non-stock kits are not stocked. When non-stock kits are added to a sales order, the items are gathered for the sale but no preliminary assembly has been performed. When a non-stock kit is listed on a sales order as a line item, its stock components are specified on a pick list and shipped to the customer. Upon shipment confirmation, the quantity of stock components is decreased while the quantities of non-stock components and kits are not tracked in any way.{br}
On release of a Sales Order invoice for a non-stock kit with stock components, the system generates an inventory issue; on release of the inventory issue, the system debits the COGS accounts of the stock components, thus updating the stock components&rsquo; costs. On the sale of a non-stock kit with only non-stock components, no inventory issue is generated.{br}
When you process a sale of a non-stock kit, its stock components are issued from inventory, and the sales revenue from all components of the kit is recorded to accounts. ==Calculation of Cost for Non-Stock Kits== The cost of a non-stock kit may include the cost of the kit itself and the costs of all stock components included in the kit. You can select one of the following cost calculation rules on in the '''Cost Calculation Basis for Non-Stock Kits''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000]) form:[anchor|#_0a245417-0290-4289-b75e-38c12b9f6352] *''Stock Component Cost'': The system will use the sum of the costs of the kit&rsquo;s stock components as the cost of a non-stock kit. You can select this rule if the kit does not include non-stock components or the value of the included non-stock components is very low. *''Non-Stock Kit Standard Cost'': The system will use the standard current cost of the non-stock kit. You can select this rule if the kit does not include stock components or the value of the included stock components is very low. *''Non-Stock Kit Standard Cost Plus Stock Component Cost'': The system will calculate the sum of the standard current cost of a non-stock kit and the costs of the stock components of this kit.
You can enter the kit standard cost directly in the '''Pending Cost''' box on the '''Price/Cost Information''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) form when you create or modify the non-stock kit.((({S:Hint}Only the ''Standard Cost'' valuation method may be assigned to non-stock kits. For more information, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods]. ))) ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Item_Costs_and_Valuation_Methods|Item Costs and Valuation Methods] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Create_Item_Class|To Create an Item Class] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_95_00|Kit Specifications] ([~/?ScreenId=IN209500|IN209500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_20_00|Non-Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202000|IN202000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_10_10_00|Sales Orders Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SO101000|SO101000])

