In addition to the basic set of properties of an inventory item in Acumatica ERP, you can create custom attributes of various types that may help your organization analyze stock movements or item sales. Custom attributes do not affect item processing in the Inventory module but provide additional information about inventory items.{br}
In this chapter, you will read about types of attributes and assignment of attributes to inventory items in Acumatica ERP. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#_69f010ce-68d7-4fae-929f-9fe3d10b1e92] {| class="checklist invisiblechecklist" | width="100%" |- | [anchor|#_a076038e-0e40-413a-96e9-2b5671d07072] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Item_Attributes|Inventory Item Attributes]
| |}

row.column:
For each stock item, Acumatica ERP provides a basic set of properties of the item. These properties include the item&rsquo;s identifier, description, price, cost, units of measure, default warehouse, and default vendor information.{br}
Stock items can have additional properties, known as ''attributes'' in Acumatica ERP, that do not affect item processing in the Inventory module but may help your organization analyze stock movements or item sales. Attributes may differ for different types of inventory items. ==Types of Attributes== In Acumatica ERP, product attributes are completely customizable. You can create attributes on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_50_00|Attributes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS205000|CS205000]) form. You can decide what attributes are needed, what values are allowed for each, and what control (type of element) is used to implement the attribute on the interface. Attributes may be of the following types: *'''Free text''': Users can enter any text as the attribute value. *'''Masked text''': The attribute text users enter must comply with a certain mask or validation rule (defined as a regular expression). *'''Date/time''': The user selects a date-time value. *'''Check box''': The attribute is a Boolean value, which means that the user can only select or clear it (such as ''yes/no'', ''true/false'', or ''on/off''). *'''Combo box''': The user selects the attribute value from a predefined list that consists of values you specify when you create the attribute. For each value, you specify its ID (such as ''1M''), its description (such as ''Less than 1,000,000''), and its sort order. Values with smaller sort orders are listed nearer to the top of the combo box list.
Also, you can define an attribute as an optional or required. This allows items to have no value for the attribute. Alternatively, you can define a special value such as ''None'' or ''N/A'' (not applicable) for use with such items. ==Attribute Assignment== You assign attributes at the item class level by using the '''Attributes''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) form. The same attribute can be used for one or several item classes. The attributes for a newly created item class are by default those of the parent item class. If the created item class has no parent, the default attributes are those of the class that is specified in the '''Default Stock Item Class''' box (if you are creating a stock item class) or the '''Default Non-Stock Item Class''' box (if you are creating a non-stock item class) on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form.{br}
When a user creates a new inventory item and assigns it to an item class by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form, the system will display the list of attributes assigned to the item's class. All items of the same item class will have the same set of attributes, although their values may differ for different items. For example, if you define a color attribute for an item class, each item in the class will have this attribute but the items can have different colors (or this attribute can be optional). {br}
Because item classes have different lists of attributes, users can have more complete information about each item. You can design custom reports to allow users to analyze information provided by item attributes. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_10_00|Item Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN201000|IN201000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_20_50_00|Attributes] ([~/?ScreenId=CS205000|CS205000])

Lot numbers and serial numbers are used to track certain types of inventory items as they are received, stored, manufactured, and shipped. Some products, such as food products and chemical compounds, are tracked because they have expiration dates, while other products, such as medications, are tracked because laws require manufacturers to keep accurate records about their distribution. Still other products—such as electronics, appliances, and cars—must be tracked individually from the manufacturer to the consumer because of safety and warranty issues. Acumatica ERP provides flexible numbering schemes for lot and serial numbers and gives you the option to track different products differently.{br}
In this chapter, you will find information about configuring, managing, and tracking lot and serial numbers in Acumatica ERP. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#_0372d45a-d42e-4116-8b3c-9ad005395535] {| class="checklist invisiblechecklist" | width="100%" |- | [anchor|#_956dfc5e-5a29-459b-a998-2ed7e1dfa8c0] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Lot_and_Serial_Numbers|Lot and Serial Numbers] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Lot_and_Serial_Number_Tracking|Lot and Serial Number Tracking]
| |}

Lot numbers and serial numbers are used to track certain types of inventory items as they are received, stored, manufactured, and shipped. Some products, such as food products and chemical compounds, are tracked because they have expiration dates, while other products, such as medications, are tracked because laws require manufacturers to keep accurate records about their distribution. Still other products—such as electronics, appliances, and cars—must be tracked individually from the manufacturer to the consumer because of safety and warranty issues. {br}
If the ''Lot and Serial Tracking'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can set up tracking of stock items by lot or serial number, as well as by expiration date. ([HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Lot_and_Serial_Number_Tracking|Lot and Serial Number Tracking] gives additional information about this tracking.) Acumatica ERP provides flexible numbering schemes for lot and serial numbers and gives you the option to track different products differently. It also provides different valuation methods to account for the cost of inventory for each lot or serial number. Kits may have their own serial numbers while also containing components that have lot and serial numbers. {br}{TOC} ==Lot and Serial Numbers== A serial number is a unique number that identifies a single item of stock, such as a camera, DVD player, or bicycle. Serial numbers can be generated by the system, or you can assign them manually on a per-item basis so the system reflects the numbers provided by the manufacturer. {br}
A lot number is a unique identification code assigned to a specific quantity or ''lot'' of a product. A lot number includes the information about the inventory item model and may include an expiration date. The same lot number is assigned to every item of the lot. The lot size is generally specified on the purchase order or on the '''Vendor Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) form. ((({S:Hint}Lot numbers can be tracked only for base units. ))) If component parts as well as assembled kits have lot or serial numbers, your company will know precisely which assembled kits contain any component, if this information is requested by the component manufacturer. ==Lot and Serial Classes== The settings of lot and serial numbers are defined at the item class level by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000]) form. Lot or serial classes are divided into three groups based on their tracking method: *Classes of items that are not tracked by either number; you should define at least one lot/serial class for such items *Classes whose items are tracked by lot numbers *Classes whose items are tracked by serial numbers
Use the following guidelines when you&rsquo;re deciding which lot/serial classes to create: *Define a class intended for items that will not be tracked. This class can be used as the default lot/serial class if most inventory items will not be tracked by any property. *Create separate groups of classes for items with serial numbers and items with lot numbers. Within each group, create separate classes for items with expiration dates and without them, if both types of products are involved in your business. *Use separate classes to group items to which serial numbers are assigned on receipt and on usage. Items purchased for further sale generally are assigned numbers on their receipt, while items produced (and kits assembled) are assigned numbers on their sale or usage. *Consider using additional classes for items with different issue methods: FIFO, sequential, date, and custom.
Acumatica ERP provides flexible tools that you can use to configure different templates for generating such numbers, or you can manually enter them. Other settings of the lot/serial classes define how and when the numbers will be generated, whether expiration dates are assigned and tracked, and what order is used for issuing the items from warehouses. ==Lot/Serial Class Settings== When creating a class whose items will be tracked by lot or serial numbers, you specify the following information on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000]) form: *Which tracking method is used for the class. *Whether to track expiration dates or not. *What is the maximum number of lot or serial numbers that can be assigned at once, which is controlled by the '''Auto-Generate Number Batch Size''' setting. If a larger quantity of the item is specified on a document, only the maximum number of lot/serial numbers will be generated, with the excess quantity remaining with unassigned numbers. You can initiate the assignment of lot/serial numbers for an unassigned quantity of the item manually. *How the numbers are assigned. The assignment method is one of the following: **''When Received'': Items get lot/serial numbers when they are received, and they&rsquo;re handled as lot- or serial-numbered items throughout their &ldquo;life&ldquo; in stock until they are issued from a warehouse. **''When Used'': The lot/serial numbers are not assigned to items until they&rsquo;re issued from stock or used in kit assembly; before that, items are handled as non-tracked stock items. If such an item is returned by a customer, this item can be issued again with the same lot or serial number. *What the issue method is for items of the class, which can be one of the following: **''FIFO'': Lot/serial numbers are picked for issue by receipt date (oldest first). **''LIFO'': Lot/serial numbers are picked for issue by receipt date (newest first). **''Sequential'': Lot/serial numbers are picked in sequential order. **''Expiration'': Lot/serial numbers are picked by expiration date (faster-expiring first). We recommend that you select ''Expiration'' as the issue method for items with a rather short shelf life. **''Custom'' (''User-Enterable''): This method is not implemented in the current version.
==Segmented Structure of Lot And Serial Numbers== Lot and serial numbers are segmented, and you can decide how many and what kind of segments there should be. Acumatica ERP supports the following types of segments: *''Constant'': A segment of this type is a predefined alphanumeric string to be used in all lot or serial numbers generated for items of the class. *''Date'': A segment of this type will be generated based on the relevant date (of receipt or of usage), which may include day, month number, month name, and two- or four-digit year value. *''Auto-incremental value'': A value for the segment of this type is automatically computed by the system when a new lot/serial number is generated, because a numbering sequence is actually used. ((({S:Warn}To correctly configure lot or serial numbers for a class, assign a numbering sequence to one of the segments. ))) The same numbering sequence can be used for all items of the class if you select the '''Share Auto-Incremental Value Between All Class Items''' check box. In this case, sequential numbers may be assigned to different inventory items, which in some cases may be inconvenient. If this check box is not selected, on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form, for each inventory item of the class, you can specify which will have the same segment auto-numbered, a separate auto-incremental values—that is, an individual initial string of digits to be auto-incremented. To prevent generation of similar serial numbers for different items of the same class, consider using different initial strings (auto-incremented values) for items of the class, so that numbers for different items will be generated in non-intersecting ranges. {br}
For example, imagine that there are 10 items in a lot/serial class. During a year, no more than 1000 units of any item pass through warehouses. The auto-incremental values for items can be selected in the following way: 000000, 100000, 200000, ... , 900000. If additional items (beyond 10) will be added to the class, new auto-incremental values can be used for them. ==Assignment to Stock Items== Each stock item is assigned to a lot/serial class that defines whether the items will be tracked by lot or serial numbers. Stock items are assigned to lot/serial classes using the '''General Settings''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form. {br}
After that, lot and serial numbers, if any should be assigned, are generated automatically by the system when the inventory items are received, issued, or assembled, depending on the assignment method of the lot/serial class. When such items are moved (transferred between warehouses or sold), you can invoke the '''Allocations''' dialog box to view or specify particular lot or serial numbers to be transferred or picked for the sales order, depending on the issue method selected for the class. ((({S:Hint}You cannot change an assignment method selected for the lot/serial class for another assignment method if there are any history transactions with any item of the class, or any unreleased document that includes an item of the class, or any non-zero quantity of any item of the class at any location. ))) ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_The_Cost_of_Inventory|The Cost of Inventory] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Lot_and_Serial_Number_Tracking|Lot and Serial Number Tracking] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] ([~/?ScreenId=IN202500|IN202500]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000])

With the ''Lot and Serial Tracking'' feature enabled in your system, you can track inventory items by either lot or serial numbers, as well as by expiration dates. You can assign lot or serial numbers to products as they are received or used. ((({S:Hint}You cannot change an assignment method selected for the lot/serial class for another assignment method if there are any history transactions with any item of the class, or any unreleased document that includes an item of the class, or any non-zero quantity of any item of the class at any location. ))) Items to be tracked should be assigned to specific lot/serial classes you&rsquo;ve created on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_70_00|Lot/Serial Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN207000|IN207000]) form. For more details on configuring lot and serial numbers, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Lot_and_Serial_Numbers|Lot and Serial Numbers]. {br}{TOC} ==Assigning Lot Numbers on Receipts== Generally, lot numbers are assigned to items when they are received (with the ''When Received'' assignment method). Lot numbers are used to track perishable goods, chemical and medical supplies, and other goods for which laws require companies to maintain accurate records and traceability to the end customer. {br}
The lot size for each lot-numbered stock item is specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_20_10_00|Vendor Inventory] ([~/?ScreenId=PO201000|PO201000]) form. When you enter a purchase receipt for lot-numbered items, you can specify the quantities of items in units of measure other than base units; in this case, the system converts the quantity on receipt to base units and calculates how many lots are received. The system then generates lot numbers according to the lot number templates specified by the lot/serial classes the items are assigned to. The same lot number is assigned to all base units in the lot. {br}
For the receipt, you can run the [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_92_00|Inventory Item Labels] ([~/?ScreenId=IN619200|IN619200]) report to print labels for products. This can be useful for physical inventories and for picking items for sales orders. {br}
Consider this example of unit conversion: Suppose that you create a purchase receipt for two crates of lot-numbered goods for which the following information applies: *The base unit is ''PIECE''. *A crate contains 12 pieces. *The lot size is a crate.
For this transaction, the system will generate two lot numbers and create two receipt transactions. ==Tracking Lot Numbers on Sales Orders== If your company produces or resells items with expiration dates, you can assign lot numbers to items on their sale (with the ''When Used '' assignment method). When you enter a lot-numbered stock item on a sales order, the system generates the list of particular lot numbers with quantities of the item in the base unit.{br}
For items with the ''When Received'' assignment method, the item&rsquo;s specific units are picked in accordance with the issue method assigned to the item&rsquo;s lot/serial class as follows: *''FIFO'': The units with the earliest receipt dates will be selected for the order. *''LIFO'': The units with the latest receipt dates will be selected for the order. *''Expiration'': The units with the earliest expiration dates will be selected for the order. *''Sequential'': The units from the top of the list (with lot numbers ordered sequentially) will be selected for the order. *''Custom'': The units with lot numbers you manually select will be used for the order.
If the sales unit is smaller than the base unit for an item tracked by lot number (that is, the base unit consists of several sales units), the item may be sold in fractional quantities with the specified lot number. ==Assigning Serial Numbers on Receipts== With serialized inventory (inventory items with serial numbers), you can maintain the history of any serial number, track its costs and find the customer in case of recall. {br}
For stock items with serial numbers, the base unit should be the smallest unit of measure used for the item; in such cases, the same unit is used as the purchase unit, sales unit, and the base unit. ((({S:Hint}To enable tracking of serial numbers from vendor to customer, for items with the ''When Received'' method, you can configure the serial numbers so that one of the segments of serial numbers can be used for these manufacturer&rsquo;s numbers. ))) When you enter a purchase receipt that includes a serial-numbered item, if a quantity was specified in purchase units that differ from the base units, the system will perform quantity conversion to the base units and will generate a serial number for each base unit of the product. To generate the serial numbers and to view the generated serial numbers, invoke the '''Allocations''' dialog box on the '''Document Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\PO_30_20_00|Purchase Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=PO302000|PO302000]) form. {br}
As an example of unit conversion, imagine that you enter a purchase receipt for a case of serialized items for which the base unit is ''PIECE'', and the purchase unit is ''BOX'', which includes 10 ''PIECES''. For the item, on receipt, the system will generate 10 serial numbers. ==Tracking Serial Numbers on Sales Orders== When the items with the ''When Received'' assignment method are sold, their serial numbers must be specified in a sales order. When you enter a sales order with a serialized stock item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form, the particular units will be selected in accordance with the issue method selected for the lot/serial class of the stock item. To select the serial numbers, open the '''Allocations ''' dialog box on the '''Document Details''' tab of this form. {br}
For stock items with the ''When Used'' assignment method, the serial numbers must be specified when the items are listed on the sales order. Depending on the item&rsquo;s lot/serial class, you can manually enter the numbers or generate them. To enter or to generate the serial numbers and to view the serial numbers, invoke the '''Allocations''' dialog box on the '''Document Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form. ((({S:Hint}To enable tracking of serial numbers from vendor to customer, for items with the ''When Used'' assignment method you can configure the lot/serial class so that the manufacturer&rsquo;s serial numbers can be assigned directly as serial numbers. ))) If an item with the serial number assigned on issue (with the ''When Used'' assignment method) is returned by a customer, the item can be issued again with the same serial number.((({S:Hint}When you enter a vendor return, the unit of measure that appears by default is the purchase UOM (unit of the measure) if the purchase UOM was defined for the item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form, and you must specify the particular serial numbers of each returned base UOM. ))) ==Tracking Expiration Dates== Acumatica ERP provides the ability to track the expiration date for each lot and serial number. The expiration date is specified on receipt of the items, and the same date is assigned to all items of a lot. The expiration date can be assigned to each item with a serial number individually. For a lot/serial class whose items are tracked by expiration dates, you can select the ''Expiration'' issue method to automatically issue items with the earliest expiration dates, thus minimizing losses. {br}
For the inventory items with tracked expiration dates, the quantity of expired items is calculated automatically. The quantities of expired inventory can be monitored with the help of reports and inquiries, so you can promptly discard the expired items. ==Tracking Inventory by Using Inquiries and Reports == The inquiry forms and reports in the Inventory module, listed below, provide various information about the lot/serial numbers, so that you can view how the item is allocated, and you can easily locate any item by its lot or serial number: *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_70_00|Inventory Lot/Serial History] ([~/?ScreenId=IN407000|IN407000]): Use this form to find the required item's location by the lot or serial number assigned. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]): Use this form to view how the item is allocated: the quantities at specific locations, on sales orders and purchase orders, and in transit between warehouses. *[HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_30_00|Lot/Serial Numbers] ([~/?ScreenId=IN613000|IN613000]): Use this report to view the list of items (with their specific lot or serial numbers) located at the selected warehouse or particular location.
