*[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Posting_Classes__Definition_and_Usage|Posting Classes in Inventory]

Inventory issues allow your organization to track stock levels at warehouses. If your organization uses the Sales Orders module, Acumatica ERP automatically generates inventory issues upon release of sales orders, customer returns, credit and debit memos, and kit assembly documents. {br}
Also, you can create inventory issues that are not linked to sales in the following situations: [anchor|#ul_gc5_c2b_dv] *To remove expired or damaged goods *To return excessively issued goods
If the Sales Orders module is not used, or in some other cases, you can create inventory issues to account for sales and returns.{br}{TOC} ==Types of Issue Lines== Inventory issues may decrease or increase inventory, depending on the transaction type of the issue lines.{br}
The following transaction types are available for issues:[anchor|#ul_x53_vq4_3v] *''Issue'': Indicates that the specified quantity of the inventory item is issued from inventory. Transactions of this type are generated from the purchase returns and can be created directly in the Inventory module to account for expired goods. The quantities of stock items on the issues of this type decrease the on-hand quantities of these items and decrease the total costs of the items in inventory by the amount specified in the '''Ext. Cost''' box. *''Return'': Indicates that the specified quantity of the stock item was returned to inventory. Transactions of this type are generated from customer return orders of the ''RM'' and ''RR'' order types. Issues of this type can be created to return the excessively issued items. The quantities of returned items increase the on-hand quantities of stock items and the total costs. *''Invoice'': Indicates that the specified quantity of the inventory item is issued based on an invoice. Generally, the system generates issues of this type when you are fulfilling the sales orders; also, you can create these issues manually. The quantity of inventory in this transaction will be subtracted from the quantity of the item available at the warehouse. *:((({S:Hint}If the ''Advanced SO Invoices'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, the system generates issues of the ''Invoice'' type on release of the direct sales invoices. For more information, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_scn_Direct_Sale|Processing Direct Sales and Returns]. ))) *''Debit Memo'': Indicates that the specified quantity of the inventory item is issued from inventory; the system generates transactions of this type of transaction on release of the appropriate documents. The quantity of the item in this transaction will be deducted from the on-hand quantity of the item. Transactions of this type can also be entered manually. *''Credit Memo'': Indicates that the specified quantity of the stock item is received to inventory; transactions of this type are generated by the system during the processing of customer returns of the ''RC (Return for Credit)'' type and can be entered manually. The quantity of the item in this transaction increases the on-hand quantity. *:((({S:Hint}If the ''Advanced SO Invoices'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, the system generates issues of the ''Credit Memo'' type on release of the direct sales invoices with return lines. For more information, see [HelpRoot_OrderMgmt\SO__con_scn_Direct_Sale|Processing Direct Sales and Returns]. )))
==Data Entry== You can view, edit, and create inventory issues by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_20_00|Issues] ([~/?ScreenId=IN302000|IN302000]) form. A new inventory issue, whether automatically generated or created manually, is assigned a reference number according to the numbering sequence that is specified in the '''Issue Numbering Sequence''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form.{br}
For each line of a new issue, you enter the following information:[anchor|#ul_qpy_mh4_3v] *'''Tran. Type''', which determines how the issue updates the ending inventory and which general ledger transactions are generated. *'''Inventory ID''', which identifies the stock item. If the ''Inventory Subitems'' feature is enabled in your system, the subitem is used with the inventory ID to identify the stock item. *'''UOM''', or the unit of measure. By default, the system inserts the base UOM selected for the item on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_25_00|Stock Items] form. However, if the ''Multiple Units of Measure'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, you can use any of the UOMs specified for the item. *'''Quantity''', the quantity of the item to be issued in the selected UOM. *'''Unit Cost''' or '''Ext. Cost''' (extended cost) of the issued item. You can enter the unit cost or use the default unit cost, and the system calculates the extended cost automatically as the unit cost multiplied by quantity. Alternatively, you can enter the extended cost. The default unit cost specified for a stock item on a receipt is an estimation of the actual cost retrieved from cost statistics at the moment when the item is selected for a line. Later, on release of the receipt, the system applies the correct cost according to the valuation method selected for the item. *'''Unit Price''' or '''Ext. Price''' (extended price) of the issued item, which is applicable only to lines of the ''Invoice'', ''Debit'', and ''Credit Memo'' types. You can enter the unit price or use the default unit price, and the system calculates the extended price automatically as the unit price multiplied by quantity. You can instead enter the extended price manually. *'''Reason Code''', which is required only for transactions of the ''Issue'' or ''Return'' types. The reason code defines the offset account to be updated by the issue line. The system will use the default reason code selected for issues on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form if no reason code is specified for the line. Reason codes are not used for issues generated from documents originating in the Sales Orders module.
For the procedures that describe how to enter an inventory issue, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Enter_Issue_of_Issue_Type|To Enter an Inventory Issue of the Issue Type] and [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Enter_Issue_of_Invoice_Type|To Enter an Inventory Issue of the Invoice Type]. ==Release of Issues== You can release a particular inventory issue by clicking '''Release''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_20_00|Issues] ([~/?ScreenId=IN302000|IN302000]) form. Also, you can mass-release issues (along with inventory transactions of other types) by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_10_00|Release IN Documents] ([~/?ScreenId=IN501000|IN501000]) form.{br}
If the quantity specified for any of the inventory items in the issue is greater than the ''Available for Issue'' quantity for this item in the warehouse specified for the line that contains the item, the system will not release the issue. Also, if an inventory item is tracked by lot or serial numbers, the system checks whether the specified lot or serial numbers are available in the warehouse selected in the line.{br}
If the '''Update GL''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form, on release of each inventory issue, the system generates a batch of journal entries based on the types of transactions included in the issue, and updates the availability data for the items and the cost statistics. You can view the reference number of this batch on the '''Financial Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_20_00|Issues] form: To view the details of the batch, click the reference number of the batch in the '''Batch Nbr.''' box.{br}
Released issues are read-only documents.{br}
The [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_55_00|Inventory Valuation] ([~/?ScreenId=IN615500|IN615500]) report shows the on-hand quantity and the total cost of inventory items on hand, which are updated by every released inventory issue. ==Issues Generated by Sales== If an issue is created automatically as the result of a sales order being processed, the extended cost amount usually debits a cost of goods sold account and credits an inventory account, with the accounts determined by the posting class of the stock item. Reason codes are not used for issues generated from the Sales Orders module.{br}
The unit costs specified for stock items on inventory issues are the estimations of actual costs according to the cost statistics at the moment when each item is selected in the sales order line. On release of the inventory issue, the system calculates the correct costs of the goods sold based on the valuation methods assigned to the items. ==Direct Issues== If you enter an issue manually, reason codes are required for each issue line of the ''Issue'' and ''Return'' types. Reason codes used for issues should provide offset accounts for each specific type of issues. You can specify the most appropriate reason code for each issue line; when no reason code is selected, the system automatically inserts the default reason code of the ''Issue'' usage that is specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form.{br}
With a direct issue, the extended cost amount updates the balances of the inventory account and of the offset account supplied by the reason code. The selected offset account depends on the reason of the transaction; it is a specific expense account. If the issue has been created for kit assembling, the offset account is usually an expense account, such as ''Material Expense''. If the issue has been created to remove expired goods, the offset account might be ''Expired Goods&rsquo; Costs''. {br}
For issue lines of the ''Invoice'', ''Credit Memo'', and ''Debit Memo'' types, you can specify the price and the extended price of the line item. ((({S:Hint}The '''Unit Price''' and '''Ext. Price''' values cannot be used for inventory issues of the ''Return'' and ''Issue'' types. ))) On release of such transactions (with nonzero extended prices), the system generates the following additional journal entries:[anchor|#ol_jpg_lpq_2v] *For a line of the ''Invoice'' type, the extended price amount (sales amount) is credited to the Sales account and debited to the AR Clearing account defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. *For a line of the ''Credit Memo'' or ''Debit Memo'' type, this amount is credited to the AR Clearing account and debited to the Sales account. The Sales account is determined by the posting class of the item; can be overridden by the offset account of the reason code it such code is specified.
To complete the sale to the customer or the customer return, you can later create an appropriate AR document (''Invoice'', ''Credit Memo'', or ''Debit Memo'') by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_30_10_00|Invoices and Memos] ([~/?ScreenId=AR301000|AR301000]) form, and move the sales amount from the AR Clearing account to the AR account of the customer. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Transactions|Inventory Transactions] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Posting_Classes__Definition_and_Usage|Posting Classes in Inventory]

Your organization can use inventory transfers to record stock movements between warehouses or between locations within the same warehouse. If your organization uses the Sales Order module, Acumatica ERP automatically generates inventory transfers when transfer orders are released. However, you can directly (manually) create inventory transfers too. This article describes the processing options available for inventory transfers that are created directly in the Inventory module.{br}{TOC} ==Types of Transfers== You can use transfers of the following types:[anchor|#ul_x53_vq4_3v] *''Single-Step'': The goods are transferred from the source warehouse location to the destination warehouse location. Transfers of this type can also be used to record stock moving from one location to another within the same warehouse. *''Two-Step'': The transfer operation is made in two steps: The goods are issued at a specific location in the source warehouse, and then they are received at another location in the destination warehouse. The In-Transit Account specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form is used to temporary record the cost of items in transit.
You can create, view, edit, and release inventory transfers by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_40_00|Transfers] ([~/?ScreenId=IN304000|IN304000]) form. A new inventory transfer—whether it is automatically generated or created manually, and whether it is single-step or two-step—is assigned a reference number according to the numbering sequence that is specified in the '''Transfer Numbering Sequence''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] form. ==Single-Step Transfers== For a single-step transfer, you must specify the following information on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_40_00|Transfers] form:[anchor|#ul_gjn_fjp_nv] *The source warehouse (in the '''Warehouse''' box). *The destination warehouse (in the '''To Warehouse''' box). If the items will be moved within the same warehouse, select the same warehouse as the source warehouse. *Information about the stock item to be moved: inventory ID, UOM, and quantity. *Information about the source location and the destination location.
For more details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Perform_SS_Transfer|To Create a Single-Step Transfer].{br}
You can release a particular inventory transfer by clicking '''Release''' on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_40_00|Transfers] form. Also, you can release the transfers (along with inventory transactions of other types) in bulk by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_50_10_00|Release IN Documents] ([~/?ScreenId=IN501000|IN501000]) form. {br}
When a transfer performed between locations within the same warehouse is released, the system updates the allocations and the availability data for the transferred items but does not change the item costs.((({S:Hint}No batch is generated for a single-step transfer that records item movement from one location to another within the same warehouse. ))) When a transfer performed between different warehouses is released, the system updates allocations and availability data, updates cost statistics, and generates a GL batch of the following transactions: [anchor|#ul_p4s_kfl_4v] *''Inventory'' account: Cr, COGS amount *''Inventory'' account: Dr, COGS amount
The Inventory account for each item is determined by the posting class of this item. There could be two different accounts associated with the warehouses involved in the transfer if ''Warehouse'' is selected in the '''Use Inventory/Accrual Account From''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_20_60_00|Posting Classes] ([~/?ScreenId=IN206000|IN206000]) form. If the ''Subaccounts'' feature is enabled in your system, the subaccounts used for the batch are defined by the rule specified in the '''Combine Inventory/Accrual Sub. From''' box.{br}
The [HelpRoot_ReportReference\IN_61_55_00|Inventory Valuation] ([~/?ScreenId=IN615500|IN615500]) report shows the on-hand quantity and the total cost of the inventory items on hand in each warehouse. This data is updated by each released inventory transfer that involves two warehouses. ==Two-Step Transfers== If a company has multiple warehouses located at significant distances from one another, moving stock items between warehouses may require some time. Thus, the costs of items in transit are recorded temporarily to the In-Transit account. When the items are received at the destination warehouse, their costs are transferred to the appropriate inventory account. {br}
For a two-step transfer, you must create both of the following documents:[anchor|#ol_o4y_c2g_4v] #'''Transfer of the ''2-Step'' type''': You can create this document by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_40_00|Transfers] ([~/?ScreenId=IN304000|IN304000]) form. For details, see [HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Perform_2S_Transfer|To Create a Two-Step Transfer]. #:When this inventory transfer is released, journal entries for the following GL accounts are created: [anchor|#ul_dzh_4py_nv] #*''Inventory'' account: Cr, COGS amount #*''In-Transit'' account: Dr, COGS amount #:The In-Transit account is specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_10_10_00|Inventory Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=IN101000|IN101000]) form. If the ''Subaccounts'' feature is enabled in your system, the In-Transit subaccount used for the batch is defined in the '''In-Transit Sub.''' box on the same form. #:As a result, the '''On Hand Qty.''' of the items in the source warehouse has been decreased. #'''Transfer Receipt''': Once the two-step transfer (the previous document) is released, you must create a receipt for this transfer on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_10_00|Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=IN301000|IN301000]) form by selecting the transfer by its reference number in the '''Transfer Nbr.''' box. When you do, all the information about the transferred items will be added to the transfer receipt. #:When this transfer receipt is released, the system updates the item&rsquo;s availability data, updates cost statistics, and generates a batch of the following GL transactions: #*''In-Transit'' account: Cr, COGS amount #*''Inventory'' account: Dr, COGS amount #:You can view the reference number of this batch on the '''Financial Details''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_40_00|Transfers] form: To view the details of the batch, click the reference number of the batch in the '''Batch Nbr.''' box.
As the result of receipt being released, the '''On Hand Qty.''' of the items in the destination warehouse has been increased, as you can view on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_40_20_00|Inventory Allocation Details] ([~/?ScreenId=IN402000|IN402000]) form. ==Cost Updating== The costs the transferred items will have in the destination warehouse depend on the valuation methods assigned to the items. For items with the ''Average'' and ''Standard cost'' valuation methods, the cost of an item in the destination warehouse will be the same as at the cost of the item at the source warehouse. For an item with the ''FIFO'' or ''Specific'' valuation method, a transfer receipt creates a new cost layer with the transferred quantity of the item and with the number and date of this transfer receipt. For details, see the section below. ==An Example of Cost Updating for a FIFO Item == If a stock item with the ''FIFO'' valuation method was transferred from one warehouse to another, a new cost layer for the transferred quantity is created. The history of transactions in the table below illustrates what costs the transferred items will have in the destination warehouse.[anchor|#table_vsl_r22_4v] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="7%" ! Transaction !width="17%" ! Tran. Type !width="12%" ! Date !width="12%" ! Ref. Nbr. !width="12%" ! Qty. !width="12%" ! Warehouse !width="12%" ! Unit Cost !width="12%" ! Comment |- | 1 | ''Receipt'' | ''Feb 01'' | ''RCP001'' | <tt>5</tt> | ''WHL1'' | <tt>300</tt> | A new cost layer was created. |- | 2 | ''Receipt'' | ''Feb 01'' | ''RCP001'' | <tt>7</tt> | ''WHL2'' | <tt>450</tt> | A new cost layer was created. |- | 3 | ''Transfer'' | ''Feb 08'' | ''TRAN001'' | <tt>-3</tt> | ''WHL1'' | <tt>300</tt> | A cost layer was updated; the quantity was decreased. |- | 4 | ''Transfer Receipt'' | ''Feb 09'' | ''TRREC01'' | <tt>3</tt> | ''WHL2'' | <tt>300</tt> | A new cost layer (with 3 units) was created with the date Feb 9. |} ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Inventory_Transactions|Inventory Transactions] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__con_Receipt_Processing|Inventory Receipt Processing] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Perform_SS_Transfer|To Create a Single-Step Transfer] *[HelpRoot_InvMgmt\IN__how_Perform_2S_Transfer|To Create a Two-Step Transfer]

